# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: plasma-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] In plasmas and electrolytes, the **Debye length** **$\lambda _{\text{D}}$** (**Debye radius** or **Debye–Hückel screening length**), is a measure of a charge carrier's net electrostatic effect in a solution and how far its electrostatic effect persists.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] With each Debye length the charges are increasingly electrically screened and the electric potential decreases in magnitude by e.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] A **Debye sphere** is a sphere whose radius is the Debye length.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Debye length is an important parameter in plasma physics, electrolytes, and colloids (DLVO theory).
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The Debye length for a plasma consisting of particles with density n , charge q , and temperature T is given by $\lambda _{\text{D}}^{2}=\varepsilon _{0}k_{\text{B}}T/(nq^{2})$ .
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The corresponding Debye screening wavenumber is given by $1/\lambda _{\text{D}}$ .
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The analogous quantities at very low temperatures ( $T\to 0$ ) are known as the Thomas–Fermi length and the Thomas–Fermi wavenumber, respectively.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] They are of interest in describing the behaviour of electrons in metals at room temperature and warm dense matter.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The Debye length is named after the Dutch-American physicist and chemist Peter Debye (1884–1966), a Nobel laureate in Chemistry.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The Debye length arises naturally in the description of a substance with mobile charges, such as a plasma, electrolyte solution, or semiconductor.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] In such a substance, charges naturally screen out electric fields induced in the substance, with a certain characteristic length.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] That characteristic length is the Debye length.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Its value can be mathematically derived for a system of N different species of charged particles, where the j -th species carries charge $q_{j}$ and has concentration $n_{j}(\mathbf {r} )$ at position $\mathbf {r}$ .
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The mobile charges don't only affect $\Phi (\mathbf {r} )$ , but are also affected by $\Phi (\mathbf {r} )$ due to the corresponding Coulomb force, $-q_{j}\,\nabla \Phi (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Solutions to this nonlinear equation are known for some simple systems.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Substituting this length scale into the Debye–Hückel equation and neglecting the second and third terms on the right side yields the much simplified form $\lambda _{\text{D}}^{2}\nabla ^{2}\Phi (\mathbf {r} )=\Phi (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] As the only characteristic length scale in the Debye–Hückel equation, $\lambda _{\text{D}}$ sets the scale for variations in the potential and in the concentrations of charged species.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] All charged species contribute to the Debye length in the same way, regardless of the sign of their charges.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] To illustrate Debye screening, one can consider the example of a point charge placed in a plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] For a weakly collisional plasma, Debye shielding can be introduced in a very intuitive way by taking into account the granular character of such a plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Let us imagine a sphere about one of its electrons, and compare the number of electrons crossing this sphere with and without Coulomb repulsion.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Therefore, according to Gauss theorem, the apparent charge of the first electron is smaller than in the absence of repulsion.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The larger the sphere radius, the larger is the number of deflected electrons, and the smaller the apparent charge: this is Debye shielding.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Since the global deflection of particles includes the contributions of many other ones, the density of the electrons does not change, at variance with the shielding at work next to a Langmuir probe (Debye sheath).
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Ions bring a similar contribution to shielding, because of the attractive Coulombian deflection of charges with opposite signs.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] This intuitive picture leads to an effective calculation of Debye shielding (see section II.A.2 of ).
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The assumption of a Boltzmann distribution is not necessary in this calculation: it works for whatever particle distribution function.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The calculation also avoids approximating weakly collisional plasmas as continuous media.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] An N-body calculation reveals that the bare Coulomb acceleration of a particle by another one is modified by a contribution mediated by all other particles, a signature of Debye shielding (see section 8 of ).
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] When starting from random particle positions, the typical time-scale for shielding to set in is the time for a thermal particle to cross a Debye length, i.e. the inverse of the plasma frequency.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Therefore in a weakly collisional plasma, collisions play an essential role by bringing a cooperative self-organization process: Debye shielding.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] This shielding is important to get a finite diffusion coefficient in the calculation of Coulomb scattering (Coulomb collision).
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] In space plasmas where the electron density is relatively low, the Debye length may reach macroscopic values, such as in the magnetosphere, solar wind, interstellar medium and intergalactic medium.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Alternatively, $\kappa ^{-1}={\frac {1}{\sqrt {8\pi \lambda _{\text{B}}N_{\text{A}}\times 10^{-24}I}}}$ where $\lambda _{\text{B}}$ is the Bjerrum length of the medium in nm, and the factor $10^{-24}$ derives from transforming unit volume from cubic dm to cubic nm.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] For deionized water at room temperature, at pH=7, *λ*B ≈ 0.71 nm.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] There is a method of estimating an approximate value of the Debye length in liquids using conductivity, which is described in ISO Standard, and the book.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] The Debye length has become increasingly significant in the modeling of solid state devices as improvements in lithographic technologies have enabled smaller geometries.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] When doping profiles exceed the Debye length, majority carriers no longer behave according to the distribution of the dopants.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] Instead, a measure of the profile of the doping gradients provides an "effective" profile that better matches the profile of the majority carrier density.
[src:plasma-physics/debye-length] In the context of solids, Thomas–Fermi screening length may be required instead of Debye length.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Research on fusion reactors began in the 1940s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Thermonuclear fusion reactions require fuel in a plasma state and a confined environment with high temperature, pressure, and sufficient confinement time.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The relationship between these parameters is expressed by the Lawson criterion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In stars, gravity provides the conditions for fusing hydrogen isotopes.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Experimental reactors use deuterium and tritium, heavier isotopes of hydrogen, in a process known as DT fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This reaction forms a helium nucleus and an energetic neutron.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion fuel is extremely energy-dense, but tritium is scarce on Earth and decays with a half-life of about 12.3 years.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Future reactors plan to use lithium breeding blankets that generate tritium when exposed to neutron radiation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion offers advantages compared with nuclear fission.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] It produces minimal high-level radioactive waste and involves lower inherent safety risks.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] However, the process generates intense neutron radiation that gradually damages the inner walls of a reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Achieving sustained energy gain beyond breakeven and converting it efficiently into electricity remain major technical challenges.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Research focuses mainly on two methods: magnetic confinement fusion (MCF) and inertial confinement fusion (ICF).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] MCF devices use magnetic fields to contain plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Early concepts included the z-pinch, stellarator, and magnetic mirror, with the tokamak design becoming dominant after Soviet experiments in the 1960s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] ICF compresses and heats small fuel pellets using high-energy lasers, developed primarily since the 1970s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The largest active projects are ITER in France and the National Ignition Facility in the United States.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Commercial and academic teams are also studying alternatives such as magnetized target fusion and modern stellarator designs.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The terms "fusion experiment" and "fusion device" refer to the collection of technologies used for scientific investigation of plasma, and technical advancement.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Not all are capable of, or routinely used for, producing thermonuclear reactions i.e. fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The term "fusion reactor" is used interchangeably to mean the above experiments, or to mean a hypothetical power-producing version, at the center of a commercial power plant, requiring additions such as a breeding blanket and heat engine.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion reactions occur when two or more atomic nuclei come close enough for long enough that the nuclear force pulling them together exceeds the electrostatic force pushing them apart, fusing them into heavier nuclei.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] For nuclei heavier than iron-56, the reaction is endothermic, requiring an input of energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The heavy nuclei bigger than iron have many more protons resulting in a greater repulsive force.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] For nuclei lighter than iron-56, the reaction is exothermic, releasing energy when they fuse.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Since hydrogen has a single proton in its nucleus, it requires the least effort to attain fusion, and yields the most net energy output.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Also, since it has one electron, hydrogen is the easiest fuel to fully ionize.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The repulsive electrostatic interaction between nuclei operates across larger distances than the strong force, which has a range of roughly one femtometer—the diameter of a proton or neutron.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The fuel atoms must be supplied enough kinetic energy to approach one another closely enough for the strong force to overcome the electrostatic repulsion in order to initiate fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The "Coulomb barrier" is the quantity of kinetic energy required to move the fuel atoms near enough.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Atoms can be heated to extremely high temperatures or accelerated in a particle accelerator to produce this energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] An atom loses its electrons once it is heated past its ionization energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The resultant bare nucleus is a type of ion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The result of this ionization is plasma, which is a heated cloud of bare nuclei and free electrons that were formerly bound to them.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Plasmas are electrically conducting and magnetically controlled because the charges are separated.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This is used by several fusion devices to confine the hot particles.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] A reaction's cross section, denoted σ, measures the probability that a fusion reaction will happen.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This depends on the relative velocity of the two nuclei.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Higher relative velocities generally increase the probability, but the probability begins to decrease again at very high energies.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In a plasma, particle velocity can be characterized using a probability distribution.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] If the plasma is thermalized, the distribution looks like a Gaussian curve, or Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In this case, it is useful to use the average particle cross section over the velocity distribution.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The Lawson criterion considers the energy balance between the energy produced in fusion reactions to the energy being lost to the environment.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In order to generate usable energy, a system would have to produce more energy than it loses.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Lawson assumed an energy balance, shown below.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The rate of fusion, and thus Pfusion, depends on the temperature and density of the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The plasma loses energy through conduction and radiation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Conduction occurs when ions, electrons, or neutrals impact other substances, typically a surface of the device, and transfer a portion of their kinetic energy to the other atoms.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The rate of conduction is also based on the temperature and density.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Radiation is energy that leaves the cloud as light.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Radiation also increases with temperature as well as the mass of the ions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion power systems must operate in a region where the rate of fusion is higher than the losses.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The Lawson criterion argues that a machine holding a thermalized and quasi-neutral plasma has to generate enough energy to overcome its energy losses.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The amount of energy released in a given volume is a function of the temperature, and thus the reaction rate on a per-particle basis, the density of particles within that volume, and finally the confinement time, the length of time that energy stays within the volume.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This is known as the "triple product": the plasma density, temperature, and confinement time.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In magnetic confinement, the density is low, on the order of a "good vacuum".
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] For instance, in the ITER device the fuel density is about 1.0 × 1019 m−3, which is about one-millionth atmospheric density.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This means that the temperature and/or confinement time must increase.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion-relevant temperatures have been achieved using a variety of heating methods that were developed in the early 1970s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In modern machines, as of 2019, the major remaining issue was the confinement time.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Plasmas in strong magnetic fields are subject to a number of inherent instabilities, which must be suppressed to reach useful durations.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] One way to do this is to simply make the reactor volume larger, which reduces the rate of leakage due to classical diffusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In contrast, inertial confinement systems approach useful triple product values via higher density, and have short confinement intervals.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In NIF, the initial frozen hydrogen fuel load has a density less than water that is increased to about 100 times the density of lead.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In these conditions, the rate of fusion is so high that the fuel fuses in the microseconds it takes for the heat generated by the reactions to blow the fuel apart.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Although NIF is also large, this is a function of its "driver" design, not inherent to the fusion process.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Multiple approaches have been proposed to capture the energy that fusion produces.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The commonly targeted D–T reaction releases much of its energy as fast-moving neutrons.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Electrically neutral, the neutron is unaffected by the confinement scheme.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In most designs, it is captured in a thick "blanket" of lithium surrounding the reactor core.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] When struck by a high-energy neutron, the blanket heats up.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] It is then actively cooled with a working fluid that drives a turbine to produce power.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Another design proposed to use the neutrons to breed fission fuel in a blanket of nuclear waste, a concept known as a fission-fusion hybrid.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In these systems, the power output is enhanced by the fission events, and power is extracted using systems like those in conventional fission reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Designs that use other fuels, notably the proton-boron aneutronic fusion reaction, release much more of their energy in the form of charged particles.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In these cases, power extraction systems based on the movement of these charges are possible.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Direct energy conversion was developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL) in the 1980s as a method to maintain a voltage directly using fusion reaction products.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This has demonstrated energy capture efficiency of 48 percent.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Plasma is an ionized gas that conducts electricity.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In bulk, it is modeled using magnetohydrodynamics, which is a combination of the Navier–Stokes equations governing fluids and Maxwell's equations governing how magnetic and electric fields behave.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] When used alone, in isolation, these methods inherently consume more power than they can provide via fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Many approaches, equipment, and mechanisms are employed across multiple projects to address fusion heating, measurement, and power production.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] A deep reinforcement learning system has been used to control a tokamak-based reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The system was able to manipulate the magnetic coils to manage the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The system was able to continuously adjust to maintain appropriate behavior (more complex than step-based systems).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In 2014, Google began working with California-based fusion company TAE Technologies to control the Joint European Torus (JET) to predict plasma behavior.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] DeepMind has also developed a control scheme with TCV.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Researchers at Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory (PPPL) and Princeton University made significant advances using artificial intelligence to control plasma in a tokamak, achieving high confinement without harmful edge energy bursts (known edge-localized modes) on two tokamaks: DIII-D and KSTAR.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Data gathered from the Diag2Diag research also provided new support for a leading theory about controlling plasma disruptions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The diagnostics of a fusion scientific reactor are extremely complex and varied.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The diagnostics required for a fusion power reactor will be various but less complicated than those of a scientific reactor as by the time of commercialization, many real-time feedback and control diagnostics will have been perfected.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] However, the operating environment of a commercial fusion reactor will be harsher for diagnostic systems than in a scientific reactor because continuous operations may involve higher plasma temperatures and higher levels of neutron irradiation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In many proposed approaches, commercialization will require the additional ability to measure and separate diverter gases, for example helium and impurities, and to monitor fuel breeding, for instance the state of a tritium breeding liquid lithium liner.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The following are some basic techniques.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Neutron blankets absorb neutrons, which heats the blanket.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Confinement refers to all the conditions necessary to keep a plasma dense and hot long enough to undergo fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] To produce self-sustaining fusion, part of the energy released by the reaction must be used to heat new reactants and maintain the conditions for fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Magnetic confinement fusion uses magnetic fields to confine the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In a magnetic mirror reactor, a configuration of electromagnets is used to create an area with an increasing density of magnetic field lines at either end of the confinement volume.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Particles approaching the ends experience an increasing force that eventually causes them to reverse direction and return to the confinement area, like light reflected from a mirror.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The most famous was the magnetic mirror machines, a series of devices built at LLNL from the 1960s to the 1980s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Other examples include magnetic bottles and the biconic cusp.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Because the mirror machines were straight, they had some advantages over ring-shaped designs.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The mirrors were easier to construct and maintain and direct conversion energy capture was easier to implement.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Poor confinement has led this approach to be abandoned, except in the polywell design.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Magnetic loops bend the field lines back on themselves, either in circles or more commonly in nested toroidal surfaces.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The most highly developed systems of this type are the tokamak, the stellarator, and the reversed field pinch.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Compact toroids, especially the field-reversed configuration and the spheromak, attempt to combine the advantages of toroidal magnetic surfaces with those of a simply connected (non-toroidal) machine, resulting in a mechanically simpler and smaller confinement area.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Inertial confinement fusion is the use of rapid implosion to heat and confine plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] A shell surrounding the fuel is imploded using a direct laser blast (direct drive), a secondary x-ray blast (indirect drive), or heavy beams.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The fuel must be compressed to about 30 times solid density with energetic beams.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Direct drive can in principle be efficient, but insufficient uniformity has prevented success.:19–20 Indirect drive uses beams to heat a shell, driving the shell to radiate x-rays, which then implode the pellet.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Electrostatic confinement fusion devices use electrostatic fields.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This device has a cathode inside an anode wire cage.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Positive ions fly towards the negative inner cage, and are heated by the electric field in the process.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] If they miss the inner cage they can collide and fuse.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Ions typically hit the cathode, however, creating prohibitory high conduction losses.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion rates in fusors are low because of competing physical effects, such as energy loss in the form of light radiation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Designs have been proposed to avoid the problems associated with the cage, by generating the field using a non-neutral cloud.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] These include a plasma oscillating device, a magnetically shielded-grid, a penning trap, the polywell, and the F1 cathode driver concept.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Spin polarization of deuterium and tritium is expected to have substantially advance fusion power towards becoming a practical technology given that aligned spins make fusion more probable.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The fuels considered for fusion power are mainly the heavier isotopes of hydrogen—deuterium and tritium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Deuterium is abundant on earth in the form of semiheavy water.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Tritium, decaying with a half-life of 12 years, must be produced.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusion reactor concepts assume as a component a proposed lithium "breeding blanket" technology surrounding the reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Helium-3 is a more speculative fuel, which must be mined extraterrestrially or produced by other nuclear reactions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The protium–boron-11 reaction is extremely speculative, but minimizes neutron radiation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This reaction is common in research, industrial and military applications, usually as a neutron source.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Deuterium is a naturally occurring isotope of hydrogen and is commonly available.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The large mass ratio of the hydrogen isotopes makes their separation easy compared to the uranium enrichment process.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Tritium is a natural isotope of hydrogen, but because it has a short half-life of 12.32 years, it is hard to find, store, produce, and is expensive.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The reactant neutron is supplied by the D–T fusion reaction shown above, and the one that has the greatest energy yield.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The reaction with 6Li is exothermic, providing a small energy gain for the reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The reaction with 7Li is endothermic, but does not consume the neutron.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Neutron multiplication reactions are required to replace the neutrons lost to absorption by other elements.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Leading candidate neutron multiplication materials are beryllium and lead, but the 7Li reaction helps to keep the neutron population high.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Natural lithium is mainly 7Li, which has a low tritium production cross section compared to 6Li so most reactor designs use breeding blankets with enriched 6Li.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The neutron flux expected in a commercial D–T fusion reactor is about 100 times that of fission power reactors, posing problems for material design.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] After a series of D–T tests at JET, the vacuum vessel was sufficiently radioactive that it required remote handling for the year following the tests.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In a production setting, the neutrons would react with lithium in the breeding blanket composed of lithium ceramic pebbles or liquid lithium, yielding tritium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The energy of the neutrons ends up in the lithium, which would then be transferred to drive electrical production.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The lithium blanket protects the outer portions of the reactor from the neutron flux.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Newer designs, the advanced tokamak in particular, use lithium inside the reactor core as a design element.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The plasma interacts directly with the lithium, preventing a problem known as "recycling".
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The advantage of this design was demonstrated in the Lithium Tokamak Experiment.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Fusing two deuterium nuclei is the second easiest fusion reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This reaction is also common in research.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The optimum energy to initiate this reaction is 15 keV, only slightly higher than that for the D–T reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The first branch produces tritium, so that a D–D reactor is not tritium-free, even though it does not require an input of tritium or lithium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Unless the tritons are quickly removed, most of the tritium produced is burned in the reactor, which reduces the handling of tritium, with the disadvantage of producing more, and higher-energy, neutrons.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The neutron from the second branch of the D–D reaction has an energy of only 2.45 MeV (0.393 pJ), while the neutron from the D–T reaction has an energy of 14.1 MeV (2.26 pJ), resulting in greater isotope production and material damage.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] When the tritons are removed quickly while allowing the 3He to react, the fuel cycle is called "tritium suppressed fusion".
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The removed tritium decays to 3He with a 12.32-year half-life.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] By recycling the 3He decay product into the reactor, the fusion reactor does not require materials resistant to fast neutrons.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Assuming complete removal of tritium and 3He recycling, only 6% of the fusion energy is carried by neutrons.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The tritium-suppressed D–D fusion requires an energy confinement that is 10 times longer compared to D–T and double the plasma temperature.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This reaction produces 4He and a high-energy proton.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] As with the p-11B aneutronic fusion fuel cycle, most of the reaction energy is released as charged particles, reducing activation of the reactor housing and potentially allowing more efficient energy harvesting (via any of several pathways).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In practice, D–D side reactions produce a significant number of neutrons, leaving p-11B as the preferred cycle for aneutronic fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Both material science problems and non-proliferation concerns are greatly diminished by aneutronic fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Theoretically, the most reactive aneutronic fuel is 3He.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] However, obtaining reasonable quantities of 3He implies large scale extraterrestrial mining on the Moon or in the atmosphere of Uranus or Saturn.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Therefore, the most promising candidate fuel for such fusion is fusing the readily available protium (i.e. a proton) and boron.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Side reactions are likely to yield neutrons that carry only about 0.1% of the power,:177–182 which means that neutron scattering is not used for energy transfer and material activation is reduced several thousand-fold.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The optimum temperature for this reaction of 123 keV is nearly ten times higher than that for pure hydrogen reactions, and energy confinement must be 500 times better than that required for the D–T reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In addition, the power density is 2500 times lower than for D–T, although per unit mass of fuel, this is still considerably higher compared to fission reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Because the confinement properties of the tokamak and laser pellet fusion are marginal, most proposals for aneutronic fusion are based on radically different confinement concepts, such as the Polywell and the dense plasma focus.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In 2013, a research team led by Christine Labaune at École Polytechnique, reported a new fusion rate record for proton-boron fusion, with an estimated 80 million fusion reactions during a 1.5 nanosecond laser fire, 100 times greater than reported in previous experiments.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Structural material stability is a critical issue.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Materials that can survive the high temperatures and neutron bombardment experienced in a fusion reactor are considered key to success.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The principal issues are the conditions generated by the plasma, neutron degradation of wall surfaces, and the related issue of plasma-wall surface conditions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Reducing hydrogen permeability is seen as crucial to hydrogen recycling and control of the tritium inventory.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Materials with the lowest bulk hydrogen solubility and diffusivity provide the optimal candidates for stable barriers.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] A few pure metals, including tungsten and beryllium, and compounds such as carbides, dense oxides, and nitrides have been investigated.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Research has highlighted that coating techniques for preparing well-adhered and perfect barriers are of equivalent importance.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The most attractive techniques are those in which an ad-layer is formed by oxidation alone.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Alternative methods utilize specific gas environments with strong magnetic and electric fields.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Assessment of barrier performance represents an additional challenge.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Classical coated membranes gas permeation continues to be the most reliable method to determine hydrogen permeation barrier (HPB) efficiency.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In a plasma that is embedded in a magnetic field (known as a magnetized plasma) the fusion rate scales as the magnetic field strength to the 4th power.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] For this reason, many fusion companies that rely on magnetic fields to control their plasma are trying to develop high temperature superconducting devices.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] In 2021, SuperOx, a Russian and Japanese company, developed a new manufacturing process for making superconducting YBCO wire for fusion reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This new wire was shown to conduct between 700 and 2000 Amps per square millimeter.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The company was able to produce 186 miles of wire in nine months.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Even on smaller production scales, the containment apparatus is blasted with matter and energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Depending on the approach, these effects may be higher or lower than fission reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Depending on the approach, other considerations such as electrical conductivity, magnetic permeability, and mechanical strength matter.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Materials must also not end up as long-lived radioactive waste.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] For long term use, each atom in the wall is expected to be hit by a neutron and displaced about 100 times before the material is replaced.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] These high-energy neutron collisions with the atoms in the wall result in the absorption of the neutrons, forming unstable isotopes of the atoms.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] When the isotope decays, it may emit alpha particles, protons, or gamma rays.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Alpha particles, once stabilized by capturing electrons, form helium atoms which accumulate at grain boundaries and may result in swelling, blistering, or embrittlement of the material.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Tungsten is widely regarded as the optimal material for plasma-facing components in next-generation fusion devices due to its unique properties and potential for enhancements.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Its low sputtering rates and high melting point make it particularly suitable for the high-stress environments of fusion reactors, allowing it to withstand intense conditions without rapid degradation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Additionally, tungsten's low tritium retention through co-deposition and implantation is essential in fusion contexts, as it helps to minimize the accumulation of this radioactive isotope.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Liquid metals (lithium, gallium, tin) have been proposed, e.g., by injection of 1–5 mm thick streams flowing at 10 m/s on solid substrates.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Graphite features a gross erosion rate due to physical and chemical sputtering amounting to many meters per year, requiring redeposition of the sputtered material.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The redeposition site generally does not exactly match the sputter site, allowing net erosion that may be prohibitive.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] An even larger problem is that tritium is redeposited with the redeposited graphite.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] The tritium inventory in the wall and dust could build up to many kilograms, representing a waste of resources and a radiological hazard in case of an accident.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Graphite found favor as material for short-lived experiments, but appears unlikely to become the primary plasma-facing material (PFM) in a commercial reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Ceramic materials such as silicon carbide (SiC) have similar issues like graphite.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Tritium retention in silicon carbide plasma-facing components is approximately 1.5–2 times higher than in graphite, resulting in reduced fuel efficiency and heightened safety risks in fusion reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] SiC tends to trap more tritium, limiting its availability for fusion and increasing the risk of hazardous accumulation, complicating tritium management.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Furthermore, the chemical and physical sputtering of SiC remains significant, contributing to tritium buildup through co-deposition over time and with increasing particle fluence.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] As a result, carbon-based materials have been excluded from ITER, DEMO, and similar devices.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Tungsten's sputtering rate is orders of magnitude smaller than carbon's, and tritium is much less incorporated into redeposited tungsten.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] However, tungsten plasma impurities are much more damaging than carbon impurities, and self-sputtering can be high, requiring the plasma in contact with the tungsten not be too hot (a few tens of eV rather than hundreds of eV).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Tungsten also has issues around eddy currents and melting in off-normal events, as well as some radiological issues.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Recent advances in materials for containment apparatus materials have found that certain ceramics can actually improve the longevity of the material of the containment apparatus.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Studies on MAX phases, such as titanium silicon carbide, show that under the high operating temperatures of nuclear fusion, the material undergoes a phase transformation from a hexagonal structure to a face-centered-cubic (FCC) structure, driven by helium bubble growth.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Helium atoms preferentially accumulate in the Si layer of the hexagonal structure, as the Si atoms are more mobile than the Ti–C slabs.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] As more atoms are trapped, the Ti–C slab is peeled off, causing the Si atoms to become highly mobile interstitial atoms in the new FCC structure.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Lattice strain induced by the He bubbles cause Si atoms to diffuse out of compressive areas, typically towards the surface of the material, forming a protective silicon dioxide layer.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Doping vessel materials with iron silicate has emerged as a promising approach to enhance containment materials in fusion reactors, as well.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This method targets helium embrittlement at grain boundaries, a common issue that arises as helium atoms accumulate and form bubbles.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] Over time, these bubbles coalesce at grain boundaries, causing them to expand and degrade the material's structural integrity.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] By contrast, introducing iron silicate creates nucleation sites within the metal matrix that are more thermodynamically favorable for helium aggregation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p01] This localized congregation around iron silicate nanoparticles induces matrix strain rather than weakening grain boundaries, preserving the material's strength and longevity.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Accident potential and effect on the environment are critical to social acceptance of nuclear fusion, also known as a social license.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion reactors are not subject to catastrophic meltdown.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It requires precise and controlled temperature, pressure and magnetic field parameters to produce net energy, and any damage or loss of required control would rapidly quench the reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion reactors operate with seconds or even microseconds worth of fuel at any moment.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Without active refueling, the reactions immediately quench.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The same constraints prevent runaway reactions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Although the plasma is expected to have a volume of 1,000 m3 (35,000 ft3) or more, the plasma typically contains only a few grams of fuel.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] By comparison, a fission reactor is typically loaded with enough fuel for months or years, and no additional fuel is necessary to continue the reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This large fuel supply is what offers the possibility of a meltdown.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In magnetic containment, strong fields develop in coils that are mechanically held in place by the reactor structure.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Failure of this structure could release this tension and allow the magnet to "explode" outward.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The severity of this event would be similar to other industrial accidents or an MRI machine quench/explosion, and could be effectively contained within a containment building similar to those used in fission reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In laser-driven inertial containment, the larger size of the reaction chamber reduces the stress on materials.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Although failure of the reaction chamber is possible, stopping fuel delivery prevents catastrophic failure.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A magnet quench is an abnormal termination of magnet operation that occurs when part of the superconducting coil exits the superconducting state (becomes normal).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This can occur because the field inside the magnet is too large, the rate of change of field is too large (causing eddy currents and resultant heating in the copper support matrix), or a combination of the two.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] More rarely a magnet defect can cause a quench.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] When this happens, that particular spot is subject to rapid Joule heating from the current, which raises the temperature of the surrounding regions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This pushes those regions into the normal state as well, which leads to more heating in a chain reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The entire magnet rapidly becomes normal over several seconds, depending on the size of the superconducting coil.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This is accompanied by a loud bang as the energy in the magnetic field is converted to heat, and the cryogenic fluid boils away.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The sudden decrease of current can result in kilovolt inductive voltage spikes and arcing.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Permanent damage to the magnet is not likely to happen, but components can be damaged by localized heating, high voltages, or large mechanical forces.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In practice, magnets usually have safety devices to stop or limit the current when a quench is detected.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] If a large magnet undergoes a quench, the inert vapor formed by the evaporating cryogenic fluid can present a significant asphyxiation hazard to operators by displacing breathable air.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A large section of the superconducting magnets in CERN's Large Hadron Collider unexpectedly quenched during start-up operations in 2008, destroying multiple magnets.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In order to prevent a recurrence, the LHC's superconducting magnets are equipped with fast-ramping heaters that are activated when a quench event is detected.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The dipole bending magnets are connected in series.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Each power circuit includes 154 individual magnets, and should a quench event occur, the entire combined stored energy of these magnets must be dumped at once.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This energy is transferred into massive blocks of metal that heat up to several hundred degrees Celsius—because of resistive heating—in seconds.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A magnet quench is a "fairly routine event" during the operation of a particle accelerator.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The natural product of the fusion reaction is a small amount of helium, which is harmless to life.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Hazardous tritium is difficult to retain completely.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] ITER incorporates total containment facilities for tritium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Calculations suggest that about 1 kilogram (2.2 lb) of tritium and other radioactive gases in a typical power station would be present.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The amount is small enough that it would dilute to legally acceptable limits by the time they reached the station's perimeter fence.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The likelihood of small industrial accidents, including the local release of radioactivity and injury to staff, are estimated to be minor compared to fission.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] They would include accidental releases of lithium or tritium or mishandling of radioactive reactor components.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion reactors create far less radioactive material than fission reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Furthermore, the material it creates is less damaging biologically, and the radioactivity dissipates within a time period that is well within existing engineering capabilities for safe long-term waste storage.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In specific terms, except in the case of aneutronic fusion, the neutron flux turns the structural materials radioactive.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The amount of radioactive material at shutdown may be comparable to that of a fission reactor, with important differences.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The half-lives of fusion and neutron activation radioisotopes tend to be less than those from fission, so that the hazard decreases more rapidly.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The fusion waste's short half-life eliminates the challenge of long-term storage.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] After 500 years, the material's levels of radiotoxicity would be the same as coal ash.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Nonetheless, classification as intermediate level waste rather than low-level waste may complicate safety discussions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The choice of materials is less constrained than in conventional fission, where many materials are required for their specific neutron cross sections.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion reactors can be designed using "low activation", materials that do not easily become radioactive.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Vanadium, for example, becomes much less radioactive than stainless steel.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Carbon fiber materials are also low-activation, are strong and light, and are promising for laser-inertial reactors where a magnetic field is not required.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion power commonly proposes the use of deuterium as fuel, and many current designs also use lithium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Assuming a fusion energy output equal to the 1995 global power output of about 100 EJ/yr (= 1 × 1020 J/yr) and that this does not increase in the future, which is unlikely, then known current lithium reserves would last 3000 years.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] On the other hand, lithium from seawater would last 60 million years, and, together with utilizing a more complicated fusion process using only deuterium, would provide fuel for 150 billion years.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In some scenarios, fusion power technology could be adapted to produce materials for military purposes.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A fusion power station could produce a significant amount of tritium; tritium is used in the trigger of hydrogen bombs and in modern boosted fission weapons, but it can be produced in other ways.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The energetic neutrons from a fusion reactor could be used to breed weapons-grade plutonium or uranium for an atomic bomb (for example, by transmutation of 238 U to 239 Pu, or 232 Th to 233 U).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The theoretical and computational tools needed for hydrogen bomb design are closely related to those needed for inertial confinement fusion, but have very little in common with magnetic confinement fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The European Union spent almost €10 billion through the 1990s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] ITER represents an investment of over twenty billion dollars, and possibly tens of billions more, including in kind contributions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Under the European Union's Sixth Framework Programme, nuclear fusion research received €750 million (in addition to ITER funding), compared with €810 million for sustainable energy research, putting research into fusion power well ahead of that of any single rival technology.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The United States Department of Energy has allocated $US367M–$US671M every year since 2010, peaking in 2020, with plans to reduce investment to $US425M in its FY2021 Budget Request.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] About a quarter of this budget is directed to support ITER.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The size of the investments and time lines meant that fusion research was traditionally almost exclusively publicly funded.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, starting in the 2010s, the promise of commercializing a paradigm-changing low-carbon energy source began to attract a raft of companies and investors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2021, Commonwealth Fusion Systems (CFS) obtained $1.8 billion in scale-up funding, and Helion Energy obtained a half-billion dollars with an additional $1.7 billion contingent on meeting milestones.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Scenarios developed in the 2000s and early 2010s discussed the effects of the commercialization of fusion power on the future of human civilization.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Using nuclear fission as a guide, these saw ITER and later DEMO as bringing online the first commercial reactors around 2050 and a rapid expansion after mid-century.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Some scenarios emphasized "fusion nuclear science facilities" as a step beyond ITER.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, the economic obstacles to tokamak-based fusion power remain immense, requiring investment to fund prototype tokamak reactors and development of new supply chains, a problem which will affect any kind of fusion reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Tokamak designs appear to be labour-intensive, while the commercialization risk of alternatives like inertial fusion energy is high due to the lack of government resources.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Scenarios since 2010 note computing and material science advances enabling multi-phase national or cost-sharing "Fusion Pilot Plants" (FPPs) along various technology pathways, such as the UK Spherical Tokamak for Energy Production, within the 2030–2040 time frame.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Notably, in June 2021, General Fusion announced it would accept the UK government's offer to host the world's first substantial public-private partnership fusion demonstration plant, at Culham Centre for Fusion Energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The plant will be constructed from 2022 to 2025 and is intended to lead the way for commercial pilot plants in the late 2020s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The plant will be 70% of full scale and is expected to attain a stable plasma of 150 million degrees.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Further UK plans include a development site near Retford.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Compact reactor technology based on such demonstration plants may enable commercialization via a fleet approach from the 2030s if early markets can be located.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The widespread adoption of non-nuclear renewable energy has transformed the energy landscape.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Such renewables are projected to supply 74% of global energy by 2050.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The steady fall of renewable energy prices challenges the economic competitiveness of fusion power.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Some economists suggest fusion power is unlikely to match other renewable energy costs.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion plants are expected to face large start up and capital costs.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Moreover, operation and maintenance are likely to be costly.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] While the costs of the China Fusion Engineering Test Reactor are not well known, an EU DEMO fusion concept was projected to feature a levelized cost of energy (LCOE) of $121/MWh.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fuel costs are low, but economists suggest that the energy cost for a one-gigawatt plant would increase by $16.5 per MWh for every $1 billion increase in the capital investment in construction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] There is also the risk that easily obtained lithium will be used up making batteries.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Obtaining it from seawater would be very costly and might require more energy than the energy that would be generated.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In contrast, renewable levelized cost of energy estimates are substantially lower.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] For instance, the 2019 levelized cost of energy of solar energy was estimated to be $40–46/MWh, on shore wind was estimated at $29–56/MWh, and offshore wind was approximately $92/MWh.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, fusion power may still have a role filling energy gaps left by renewables, depending on how administration priorities for energy and environmental justice influence the market.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In the 2020s, socioeconomic studies of fusion that began to consider these factors emerged, and in 2022 EUROFusion launched its Socio-Economic Studies and Prospective Research and Development strands to investigate how such factors might affect commercialization pathways and timetables.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Similarly, in April 2023 Japan announced a national strategy to industrialise fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Thus, fusion power may work in tandem with other renewable energy sources rather than becoming the primary energy source.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In some applications, fusion power could provide the base load, especially if including integrated thermal storage and cogeneration and considering the potential for retrofitting coal plants.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] As fusion pilot plants move within reach, legal and regulatory issues must be addressed.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In September 2020, the United States National Academy of Sciences consulted with private fusion companies to consider a national pilot plant.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The following month, the United States Department of Energy, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) and the Fusion Industry Association co-hosted a public forum to begin the process.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In November 2020, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) began working with various nations to create safety standards such as dose regulations and radioactive waste handling.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In January and March 2021, NRC hosted two public meetings on regulatory frameworks.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A public-private cost-sharing approach was endorsed in the December 27 H.R.133 Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2021, which authorized $325 million over five years for a partnership program to build fusion demonstration facilities, with a 100% match from private industry.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Subsequently, the UK Regulatory Horizons Council published a report calling for a fusion regulatory framework by early 2022 in order to position the UK as a global leader in commercializing fusion power.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This call was met by the UK government publishing in October 2021 both its *Fusion Green Paper* and its *Fusion Strategy*, to regulate and commercialize fusion, respectively.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Then, in April 2023, in a decision likely to influence other nuclear regulators, the NRC announced in a unanimous vote that fusion energy would be regulated not as fission but under the same regulatory regime as particle accelerators.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Meanwhile, in February 2024 the US House of Representatives passed the Atomic Energy Advancement Act, which includes the Fusion Energy Act, which establishes a regulatory framework for fusion energy systems.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Given the potential of fusion to transform the world's energy industry and mitigate climate change, fusion science has traditionally been seen as an integral part of peace-building science diplomacy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, technological developments and private sector involvement has raised concerns over intellectual property, regulatory administration, global leadership; equity, and potential weaponization.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] These challenge ITER's peace-building role and led to calls for a global commission.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion power significantly contributing to climate change by 2050 seems unlikely without substantial breakthroughs and a space race mentality emerging, but a contribution by 2100 appears possible, with the extent depending on the type and particularly cost of technology pathways.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Developments from late 2020 onwards have led to talk of a "new space race" with multiple entrants, pitting the US against China and the UK's STEP FPP, with China now outspending the US and threatening to leapfrog US technology.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] On September 24, 2020, the United States House of Representatives approved a research and commercialization program.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The Fusion Energy Research section incorporated a milestone-based, cost-sharing, public-private partnership program modeled on NASA's COTS program, which launched the commercial space industry.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In February 2021, the National Academies published *Bringing Fusion to the U.S.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Grid*, recommending a market-driven, cost-sharing plant for 2035–2040, and the launch of the Congressional Bipartisan Fusion Caucus followed.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In October 2023, the UK-oriented Agile Nations group announced a fusion working group.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] One month later, the UK and the US announced a bilateral partnership to accelerate fusion energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Then, in December 2023 at COP28 the US announced a US global strategy to commercialize fusion energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Later the same year, the US partnered with the IAEA to launch the Fusion Energy Solutions Taskforce, to collaboratively crowdsource ideas to accelerate commercial fusion energy, in line with the US COP28 statement.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2024, both South Korea and Japan announced major initiatives to accelerate their national fusion strategies, by building electricity-generating public-private fusion plants in the 2030s, aiming to begin operations in the 2040s and 2030s respectively.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion power promises to provide more energy for a given weight of fuel than any fuel-consuming energy source currently in use.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The fuel (primarily deuterium) exists abundantly in the ocean: about 1 in 6500 hydrogen atoms in seawater is deuterium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Although this is only about 0.015%, seawater is plentiful and easy to access, implying that fusion could supply the world's energy needs for millions of years.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] First generation fusion plants are expected to use the deuterium-tritium fuel cycle.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This will require the use of lithium for breeding of the tritium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It is not known for how long global lithium supplies will suffice to supply this need as well as those of the battery and metallurgical industries.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It is expected that second generation plants will move on to the more formidable deuterium-deuterium reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The deuterium-helium-3 reaction is also of interest, but the light helium isotope is practically non-existent on Earth.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It is thought to exist in useful quantities in the lunar regolith, and is abundant in the atmospheres of the gas giant planets.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion power could be used for so-called "deep space" propulsion within the Solar System and for interstellar space exploration where solar energy is not available, including via antimatter-fusion hybrid drives.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Deuterium–tritium fusion produces helium-4 as a by-product.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Fusion power has a number of disadvantages.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Because 80 percent of the energy in any reactor fueled by deuterium and tritium appears in the form of neutron streams, such reactors share many of the drawbacks of fission reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This includes the production of large quantities of radioactive waste and serious radiation damage to reactor components.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Additionally, naturally occurring tritium is extremely rare.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] While the hope is that fusion reactors can breed their own tritium, tritium self-sufficiency is extremely challenging, not least because tritium is difficult to contain (tritium has leaked from 48 of 65 nuclear sites in the US).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In any case the reserve and start-up tritium inventory requirements are likely to be unacceptably large.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] If reactors can be made to operate using only deuterium fuel, then the tritium replenishment issue is eliminated and neutron radiation damage may be reduced.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, the probabilities of deuterium-deuterium reactions are about 20 times lower than for deuterium-tritium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Additionally, the temperature needed is about 3 times higher than for deuterium-tritium (see cross section).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The higher temperatures and lower reaction rates thus significantly complicate the engineering challenges.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The first machine to achieve controlled thermonuclear fusion was a pinch machine at Los Alamos National Laboratory called Scylla I at the start of 1958.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The team that achieved it was led by a British scientist named James Tuck and included a young Marshall Rosenbluth.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Tuck had been involved in the Manhattan project, but had switched to working on fusion in the early 1950s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] He applied for funding for the project as part of a White House sponsored contest to develop a fusion reactor along with Lyman Spitzer.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The previous year, 1957, the British had claimed that they had achieved thermonuclear fusion reactions on the Zeta pinch machine.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, it turned out that the neutrons they had detected were from beam-target interactions, not fusion, and they withdrew the claim.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A CERN-sponsored study group on controlled thermonuclear fusion met from 1958 to 1964.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This group ceased when it became clear that CERN discontinued its limited support for plasma physics.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Scylla I was a classified machine at the time, so the achievement was hidden from the public.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A traditional Z-pinch passes a current down the center of a plasma, which makes a magnetic force around the outside which squeezes the plasma to fusion conditions.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Scylla I was a θ-pinch, which used deuterium to pass a current around the outside of its cylinder to create a magnetic force in the center.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] After the success of Scylla I, Los Alamos went on to build multiple pinch machines over the next few years.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Spitzer continued his stellarator research at Princeton.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] While fusion did not immediately transpire, the effort led to the creation of the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In the early 1950s, Soviet physicists I.E.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Sakharov developed the concept of the tokamak, combining a low-power pinch device with a low-power stellarator.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Over time, the "advanced tokamak" concept emerged, which included non-circular plasma, internal diverters and limiters, superconducting magnets, operation in the "H-mode" island of increased stability, and the compact tokamak, with the magnets on the inside of the vacuum chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] during the 1980s was a key driver of fusion development.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Laser fusion was suggested in 1962 by scientists at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL), shortly after the invention of the laser in 1960.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Inertial confinement fusion experiments using lasers began as early as 1965.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Several laser systems were built at LLNL, including the Argus, the Cyclops, the Janus, the long path, the Shiva laser, and the Nova.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Laser advances included frequency-tripling crystals that transformed infrared laser beams into ultraviolet beams and "chirping", which changed a single wavelength into a full spectrum that could be amplified and then reconstituted into one frequency.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Laser research cost over one billion dollars in the 1980s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The PLT, TFTR,Tore Supra, JET, T-15, and JT-60 tokamaks were built and operated in the 1980s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 1984, Martin Peng of ORNL proposed the spherical tokamak with a much smaller radius.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It used a single large conductor in the center, with magnets as half-rings off this conductor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The aspect ratio fell to as low as 1.2.:B247:225 Peng's advocacy caught the interest of Derek Robinson, who built the Small Tight Aspect Ratio Tokamak, (START).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 1991, the Preliminary Tritium Experiment at the Joint European Torus achieved the world's first controlled release of fusion power.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 1993, TFTR became the first tokamak to conduct experiments with significant mixes of deuterium and tritium.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 1994 these experiments resulted in a discharge with the world record 10.1 MW fusion power with 39.9 MW of neutral beam heating power.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The ratio in the plasma core, Q was approximately 0.8.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 1996, Tore Supra created a plasma for two minutes with a current of almost 1 million amperes, totaling 280 MJ of injected and extracted energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 1997, JET produced a peak of 16.1 MW of fusion power (65% of heat to plasma), with fusion power of over 10 MW sustained for over 0.5 sec.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] "Fast ignition" saved power and moved ICF into the race for energy production.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2006, China's Experimental Advanced Superconducting Tokamak (EAST) test reactor was completed.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It was the first tokamak to use superconducting magnets to generate both toroidal and poloidal fields.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In March 2009, the laser-driven ICF NIF became operational.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In the 2000s, privately backed fusion companies entered the race, including TAE Technologies, General Fusion, and Tokamak Energy.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Private and public research accelerated in the 2010s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] General Fusion developed plasma injector technology and Tri Alpha Energy tested its C-2U device.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The French Laser Mégajoule began operation.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] NIF achieved net energy gain in 2013, as defined in the very limited sense as the hot spot at the core of the collapsed target, rather than the whole target.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2014, Phoenix Nuclear Labs sold a high-yield neutron generator that could sustain 5×1011 deuterium fusion reactions per second over a 24-hour period.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2015, MIT announced a tokamak it named the ARC fusion reactor, using rare-earth barium-copper oxide (REBCO) superconducting tapes to produce high-magnetic field coils that it claimed could produce comparable magnetic field strength in a smaller configuration than other designs.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In October, researchers at the Max Planck Institute of Plasma Physics in Greifswald, Germany, completed building the largest stellarator to date, the Wendelstein 7-X (W7-X).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The W7-X stellarator began Operational phase 1 (OP1.1) on December 10, 2015, successfully producing helium plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The objective was to test vital systems and understand the machine's physics.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] By February 2016, hydrogen plasma was achieved, with temperatures reaching up to 100 million Kelvin.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The initial tests used five graphite limiters.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] After over 2,000 pulses and achieving significant milestones, OP1.1 concluded on March 10, 2016.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] An upgrade followed, and OP1.2 in 2017 aimed to test an uncooled divertor.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] By June 2018, record temperatures were reached.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] W7-X concluded its first campaigns with limiter and island divertor tests, achieving notable advancements by the end of 2018.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It soon produced helium and hydrogen plasmas lasting up to 30 minutes.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The UK's Tokamak Energy's ST40 generated "first plasma".
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The next year, Eni announced a $50 million investment in Commonwealth Fusion Systems, to attempt to commercialize MIT's ARC technology.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In January 2021, SuperOx announced the commercialization of a new superconducting wire with more than 700 A/mm2 current capability.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] TAE Technologies announced results for its Norman device, holding a temperature of about 60 MK for 30 milliseconds, 8 and 10 times higher, respectively, than the company's previous devices.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In October, Oxford-based First Light Fusion revealed its projectile fusion project, which fires an aluminum disc at a fusion target, accelerated by a 9 mega-amp electrical pulse, reaching speeds of 20 kilometres per second (12 mi/s).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The resulting fusion generates neutrons whose energy is captured as heat.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] On November 8, in an invited talk to the 63rd Annual Meeting of the APS Division of Plasma Physics, the National Ignition Facility claimed to have triggered fusion ignition in the laboratory on August 8, 2021, for the first time in the 60+ year history of the ICF program.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The shot yielded 1.3 MJ of fusion energy, an over 8X improvement on tests done in spring of 2021.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] NIF estimates that 230 kJ of energy reached the fuel capsule, which resulted in an almost 6-fold energy output from the capsule.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A researcher from Imperial College London stated that the majority of the field agreed that ignition had been demonstrated.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In April 2022, First Light announced that their hypersonic projectile fusion prototype had produced neutrons compatible with fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Their technique electromagnetically fires projectiles at Mach 19 at a caged fuel pellet.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The deuterium fuel is compressed at Mach 204, reaching pressure levels of 100 TPa.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] On December 13, 2022, the US Department of Energy reported that researchers at the National Ignition Facility had achieved a net energy gain from a fusion reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The reaction of hydrogen fuel at the facility produced about 3.15 MJ of energy while consuming 2.05 MJ of input.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] However, while the fusion reactions may have produced more than 3 megajoules of energy—more than was delivered to the target—NIF's 192 lasers consumed 322 MJ of grid energy in the conversion process.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In May 2023, the United States Department of Energy (DOE) provided a grant of $46 million to eight companies across seven states to support fusion power plant design and research efforts.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] This funding, under the Milestone-Based Fusion Development Program, aligns with objectives to demonstrate pilot-scale fusion within a decade and to develop fusion as a carbon-neutral energy source by 2050.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The granted companies are tasked with addressing the scientific and technical challenges to create viable fusion pilot plant designs in the next 5–10 years.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The recipient firms include Commonwealth Fusion Systems, Focused Energy Inc., Princeton Stellarators Inc., Realta Fusion Inc., Tokamak Energy Inc., Type One Energy Group, Xcimer Energy Inc., and Zap Energy Inc.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In December 2023, the largest and most advanced tokamak JT-60SA was inaugurated in Naka, Japan.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The reactor is a joint project between Japan and the European Union.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The reactor had achieved its first plasma in October 2023.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In January 2025, EAST fusion reactor in China was reported to maintain a steady-state high-confinement plasma operation for 1066 seconds (nearly 18 minutes).
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In February 2025, the French Alternative Energies and Atomic Energy Commission (CEA) announced that its WEST tokamak had maintained a stable plasma for 1,337 seconds—over 22 minutes.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In March Energy Singularity announced that a magnet that produce a magnetic field of 21.7 T.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2026, EAST announced that it had surpassed the Greenwald plasma density limit.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The experiment pioneered plasma-wall self-organization, electron cyclotron resonance heating (ohmic start-up), management of initial fuel gas pressure, active reduction of boundary impurity sputtering and contamination from the reactor walls.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The plasma entered a density-free regime where higher density did not increase instability.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] Claims of commercially viable fusion power being relatively imminent have often attracted ridicule within the scientific community.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] A common joke is that human-engineered fusion has always been promised as 30 years away since the concept was first discussed, or that it has been "20 years away for 50 years".
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2024, Commonwealth Fusion Systems announced plans to build the world's first grid-scale commercial nuclear fusion power plant at the James River Industrial Center in Chesterfield County, Virginia, which is part of the Greater Richmond Region.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] The plant is designed to produce about 400 MW of electric power, and is intended to come online in the early 2030s.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In 2025, Helion Energy, a startup company backed by OpenAI, announced plans to build a fusion power plant in Malaga, Washington to supply power to Microsoft data centers by 2028.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] It will use extant grid infrastructure for the nearby Rock Island Dam hydroelectric plant.
[src:plasma-physics/fusion-power-p02] In January 2026, Type One Energy announced plans to build a 350MWe fusion power plant using a stellarator fusion reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The word *magnetohydrodynamics* is derived from **magneto-**, meaning magnetic field; **hydro-**, meaning water; and **dynamics**, meaning movement.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The field of MHD was initiated by Hannes Alfvén, who received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1970 for his work in the field.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The MHD description of electrically conducting fluids was first developed by Hannes Alfvén in a 1942 paper published in *Nature* titled "Existence of Electromagnetic–Hydrodynamic Waves", which outlined his discovery of what are now known as *Alfvén waves*.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In MHD, motion in the fluid is described using linear combinations of the mean motions of the individual species: the current density $\mathbf {J}$ and the center-of-mass velocity ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In a given fluid, each species $\sigma$ has a number density ⁠ $n_{\sigma }$ ⁠, mass ⁠ $m_{\sigma }$ ⁠, electric charge ⁠ $q_{\sigma }$ ⁠, and mean velocity ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{\sigma }$ ⁠.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD can be described by a set of equations consisting of a continuity equation, an equation of motion (the Cauchy momentum equation), an equation of state, Ampère's law, Faraday's law, and Ohm's law.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] As with any fluid description of a kinetic system, a closure approximation must be applied to the highest moment of the particle distribution equation.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This is often accomplished through approximations to the heat flux under conditions of adiabaticity or isothermality.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The simplest form of MHD, **ideal MHD**, assumes that the resistive term $\eta \mathbf {J}$ in Ohm's law is sufficiently small relative to the other terms that it can be taken to be zero.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This occurs in the limit of large magnetic Reynolds numbers, in which magnetic induction dominates magnetic diffusion at the velocity and length scales under consideration.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Consequently, processes in ideal MHD that convert magnetic energy into kinetic energy, referred to as *ideal processes*, cannot generate heat or increase entropy.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] A fundamental concept underlying ideal MHD is the frozen-in flux theorem, which states that the bulk fluid and the embedded magnetic field are constrained to move together such that one can be said to be "tied" or "frozen" to the other.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Therefore, any two points that move with the bulk fluid velocity and lie on the same magnetic field line will continue to lie on that field line even as the points are advected by fluid flows in the system.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The connection between the fluid and magnetic field fixes the topology of the magnetic field in the fluid.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] For example, if a set of magnetic field lines is tied into a knot, then it will remain so as long as the fluid has negligible resistivity.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This difficulty in reconnecting magnetic field lines makes it possible to store energy by moving the fluid or the source of the magnetic field.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The energy can then become available if the conditions for ideal MHD break down, allowing magnetic reconnection to release the stored energy from the magnetic field.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The resistivity due to these collisions is small.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In particular, the typical magnetic diffusion time over any length scale present in the system must be longer than any time scale of interest.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The relevant length scales are much longer than the ion skin depth and the Larmor radius perpendicular to the field, sufficiently long scales along the field to ignore Landau damping, and time scales much longer than the ion gyration time (that is, the system is smooth and slowly evolving).
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In an imperfectly conducting fluid, the magnetic field can generally move through the fluid according to a diffusion law, with the resistivity of the plasma serving as a diffusion constant.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This means that solutions to the ideal MHD equations are applicable only for a limited time within a region of a given size before diffusion becomes too significant to ignore.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] One can estimate the diffusion time across a solar active region (from collisional resistivity) to be hundreds to thousands of years, much longer than the actual lifetime of a sunspot, so it would seem reasonable to ignore the resistivity.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] By contrast, a meter-sized volume of seawater has a magnetic diffusion time measured in milliseconds.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Even in physical systems that are large and conductive enough that simple estimates of the Lundquist number suggest that the resistivity can be ignored, resistivity may still be important: many instabilities can increase the effective resistivity of the plasma by factors greater than 109.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The enhanced resistivity is usually the result of the formation of small-scale structures such as current sheets or fine-scale magnetic turbulence, introducing small spatial scales into the system over which ideal MHD breaks down and magnetic diffusion can occur rapidly.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] When this happens, magnetic reconnection may occur in the plasma, releasing stored magnetic energy as waves, bulk mechanical acceleration of material, particle acceleration, and heat.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Magnetic reconnection in highly conductive systems is important because it concentrates energy in time and space, such that gentle forces applied to a plasma over long periods of time can cause violent explosions and bursts of radiation.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] When the fluid cannot be considered completely conductive, but the other conditions for ideal MHD are satisfied, it is possible to use an extended model called resistive MHD.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This includes an extra term in Ohm's law that models the collisional resistivity.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Generally, MHD computer simulations are at least somewhat resistive because their computational grid introduces a numerical resistivity.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In many MHD systems, most of the electric current is compressed into thin, nearly two-dimensional ribbons termed current sheets.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] These can divide the fluid into magnetic domains within which the currents are relatively weak.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Current sheets in the solar corona are thought to be between a few meters and a few kilometers thick, which is quite thin compared to the magnetic domains, which are thousands to hundreds of thousands of kilometers across.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Another example occurs in the Earth's magnetosphere, where current sheets separate topologically distinct domains, isolating most of the Earth's ionosphere from the solar wind.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The wave modes derived from the MHD equations are called **magnetohydrodynamic waves,** or **MHD waves**.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] These modes have phase velocities that are independent of the magnitude of the wave vector, so they experience no dispersion.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The phase velocity depends on the angle between the wave vector ⁠ $\mathbf {k}$ ⁠ and the magnetic field ⁠ $\mathbf {B}$ ⁠.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] An MHD wave propagating at an arbitrary angle ⁠ $\theta$ ⁠ with respect to the time-independent, or bulk, field ⁠ $\mathbf {B} _{0}$ ⁠ satisfies the dispersion relation: ${\frac {\omega }{k}}=v_{\text{A}}\cos \theta$ where $v_{\text{A}}={\frac {B_{0}}{\sqrt {\mu _{0}\rho }}}$ is the Alfvén speed.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This branch corresponds to the shear Alfvén mode.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The plus branch corresponds to the fast MHD wave mode, and the minus branch corresponds to the slow MHD wave mode.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD oscillations are damped if the fluid is not perfectly conducting but has finite conductivity, or if viscous effects are present.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD waves and oscillations are popular tools for the remote diagnostics of laboratory and astrophysical plasmas, for example, the Sun's corona (coronal seismology).
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This diffusivity leads to a break in the magnetic topology; magnetic field lines can "reconnect" when they collide.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] ; this process has been shown to be important in Earth-solar magnetic interactions.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Extended MHD describes a class of phenomena in plasmas that are higher-order than resistive MHD, but can adequately be treated with a single-fluid description.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] These include the effects of Hall physics, electron pressure gradients, finite Larmor radii in the particle gyromotion, and electron inertia.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] As a result, the electron and ion momenta must be treated separately.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This description is more closely tied to Maxwell's equations because an evolution equation for the electric field exists.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Lighthill criticized the applicability of ideal or resistive MHD theory for plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] term" in Ohm's law, a frequent simplification made in magnetic fusion theory.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The most important difference is that, in the absence of field line-breaking, the magnetic field is tied to the electrons rather than to the bulk fluid.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Electron magnetohydrodynamics (EMHD) describes small-scale plasmas in which electron motion is much faster than the ion motion.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The main effects are changes in conservation laws, additional resistivity, and the importance of electron inertia.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Many effects of Electron MHD are similar to those of two-fluid MHD and Hall MHD.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD is also used for collisionless plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] , the (resistive) MHD equations can be reduced to a set of four closed scalar equations.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This allows for, among other things, more efficient numerical calculations.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This is usually not the case in fusion, space, and astrophysical plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] When this is not the case, or when interest lies in smaller spatial scales, it may be necessary to use a kinetic model that properly accounts for the non-Maxwellian shape of the distribution function.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] However, because MHD is relatively simple and captures many of the important properties of plasma dynamics, it is often qualitatively accurate and is therefore often the first model tried.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Effects that are essentially kinetic and not captured by fluid models include double layers, Landau damping, a wide range of instabilities, chemical separation in space plasmas, and electron runaway.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In the case of ultra-high-intensity laser interactions, the extremely short time scales of energy deposition mean that hydrodynamic codes fail to capture the essential physics.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Beneath the Earth's mantle lies the core, which is made up of two parts: the solid inner core and the liquid outer core.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Both contain significant quantities of iron.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The liquid outer core moves in the presence of the magnetic field, and eddies are generated within it due to the Coriolis effect.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] These eddies develop a magnetic field that boosts Earth's original magnetic field, a self-sustaining process known as the geomagnetic dynamo.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Based on the MHD equations, Glatzmaier and Paul Roberts developed a supercomputer model of the Earth's interior.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] After the simulations are run for thousands of years in virtual time, changes in Earth's magnetic field can be studied.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The simulation results are in good agreement with observations because the simulations correctly predict that the Earth's magnetic field reverses every few hundred thousand years.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] During these reversals, the magnetic field does not vanish altogether; instead, it becomes more complex.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Some monitoring stations have reported that earthquakes are sometimes preceded by a spike in ultra-low-frequency (ULF) activity.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] A notable example of this occurred before the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake in California, although a subsequent study indicated that this was little more than a sensor malfunction.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] On December 9, 2010, geoscientists announced that the DEMETER satellite observed a dramatic increase in ULF radio waves over Haiti in the month before the magnitude 7.0 Mw 2010 earthquake.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Researchers are attempting to learn more about this correlation to determine whether this method can be used as part of an earthquake early warning system.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The study of space plasmas near Earth and throughout the Solar System is known as space physics.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Researched areas within space physics encompass a wide range of topics, including the ionosphere,auroras, Earth's magnetosphere, the solar wind, and coronal mass ejections.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD provides a framework for understanding how plasma populations interact within the local geospace environment.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] One prominent use of global MHD models is space weather forecasting.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Intense solar storms have the potential to cause extensive damage to satellites and infrastructure; thus, it is crucial that such events be detected early.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The Space Weather Prediction Center (SWPC) uses MHD models to predict the arrival and impacts of space weather events at Earth.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD applies to astrophysics, including stars, the interplanetary medium (space between the planets), the interstellar medium (space between the stars), and jets.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Most astrophysical systems are not in local thermal equilibrium and therefore require an additional kinematic treatment to describe all the phenomena within the system (see Astrophysical plasma).
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Sunspots are caused by the Sun's magnetic fields, as Joseph Larmor theorized in 1919.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The solar wind, predicted by Eugene Parker, is also described by MHD.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The differential solar rotation may be the long-term effect of magnetic drag at the Sun's poles, an MHD phenomenon resulting from the Parker spiral shape of the Sun's extended magnetic field.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Previously, theories describing the formation of the Sun and planets could not explain how the Sun contains 99.87% of the mass, yet only 0.54% of the angular momentum, in the Solar System.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In a closed system, such as the cloud of gas and dust from which the Sun formed, mass and angular momentum are both conserved.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] That conservation would imply that, as the mass concentrated at the center of the cloud to form the Sun, it would spin faster, much like a skater pulling in their arms.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The high rotational speed predicted by early theories would have flung the proto-Sun apart before it could form.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] However, magnetohydrodynamic effects transfer the Sun's angular momentum to the outer solar system, slowing its rotation.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Breakdown of ideal MHD, in the form of magnetic reconnection, is thought to be the likely cause of solar flares.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The magnetic field in a solar active region above a sunspot can store energy that is suddenly released as a burst of motion, X-rays, and radiation when the main current sheet collapses and reconnects the field.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD describes a wide range of physical phenomena occurring in fusion plasmas in devices such as tokamaks and stellarators.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The Grad-Shafranov equation, derived from ideal MHD, describes the equilibrium of axisymmetric toroidal plasma in a tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In tokamak experiments, the equilibrium during each discharge is routinely calculated and reconstructed, providing information on the shape and position of the plasma controlled by currents in external coils.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD stability theory governs the operational limits of tokamaks.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] For example, ideal MHD kink modes provide hard limits on the achievable plasma beta (Troyon limit) and plasma current (set by the $q>2$ requirement for the safety factor).
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In a tokamak, instabilities also arise from resistive MHD.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] For instance, tearing modes are instabilities that arise within the framework of non-ideal MHD.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] This is an active field of research because these instabilities are the starting point for disruptions.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Magnetohydrodynamic sensors are used for precise measurements of angular velocity in inertial navigation systems such as those used in aerospace engineering.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The sensor is capable of operating in harsh environments.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD is related to engineering problems such as plasma confinement, liquid-metal cooling in nuclear reactors, and electromagnetic casting.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] A magnetohydrodynamic drive, or MHD propulsor, is a method for propelling seagoing vessels using only electric and magnetic fields, with no moving parts.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The working principle involves electrifying the propellant (gas or water), which can then be directed by a magnetic field, thereby pushing the vehicle in the opposite direction.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Although some working prototypes exist, MHD drives remain impractical.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] The first prototype of this type of propulsion was built and tested in 1965 by Steward Way, a professor of mechanical engineering at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] While on leave from his job at Westinghouse Electric, Way assigned his senior-year undergraduate students to develop a submarine using this new propulsion system.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In the early 1990s, the Ship & Ocean Foundation (Minato-ku, Tokyo) built an experimental boat, the *Yamato-1*, which used a magnetohydrodynamic drive incorporating a superconductor cooled by liquid helium and could travel at 15 km/h.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD power generation fueled by potassium-seeded coal-combustion gas showed potential for more efficient energy conversion (the absence of solid moving parts allows operation at higher temperatures) but ultimately failed due to cost-prohibitive technical difficulties.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] One major engineering problem was the abrasion-induced failure of the wall of the primary-coal combustion chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] In microfluidics, MHD is studied as a fluid pump for producing continuous, nonpulsating flow in a complex microchannel design.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] MHD can be implemented in the continuous casting of metals to suppress instabilities and control flow.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Industrial MHD problems can be modeled using the open-source software EOF-Library.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Two simulation examples are three-dimensional MHD with a free surface for electromagnetic levitation melting and liquid-metal stirring using rotating permanent magnets.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] An important task in cancer research is developing more precise methods for delivering medicine to affected areas.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] One method involves binding of medicine to biologically compatible magnetic particles (such as ferrofluids), which are guided to the target through careful placement of permanent magnets on the exterior of the body.
[src:plasma-physics/magnetohydrodynamics] Magnetohydrodynamic equations and finite element analysis are used to study interactions between magnetic fluid particles in the bloodstream and the external magnetic field.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Langmuir waves were discovered by American physicists Irving Langmuir and Lewi Tonks in the 1920s.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] They are parallel in form to Jeans instability waves, which are caused by gravitational instabilities in a static medium.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Consider an electrically neutral plasma in equilibrium, consisting of a gas of positively charged ions and negatively charged electrons.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] If one displaces an electron or a group of electrons slightly with respect to the ions, the Coulomb force pulls the electrons back, acting as a restoring force.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] where $n_{\mathrm {e} }$ is the electron number density, e is the elementary charge, $m^{*}$ is the electron effective mass, and $\varepsilon _{0}$ is the vacuum permittivity.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] This assumes infinite ion mass, a good approximation since electrons are much lighter.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] A derivation using Maxwell’s equations gives the same result via the dielectric condition $\epsilon (\omega )=0$ .
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] This is the condition for plasma transparency and wave propagation.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] In electron–positron plasmas, relevant in astrophysics, the expression must be modified.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] As the plasma frequency is independent of wavelength, Langmuir waves have infinite phase velocity and zero group velocity.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] For $m^{*}=m_{\mathrm {e} }$ , the frequency depends only on electron density and physical constants.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Metals are reflective to light below their plasma frequency, which is in the UV range (~10²³ electrons/cm³).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Hence they appear shiny in visible light.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] This is known as the Bohm–Gross dispersion relation.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] For long wavelengths, pressure effects are minimal; for short wavelengths, dispersion dominates.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] At these small scales, wave phase velocity $v_{\mathrm {ph} }=\omega /k$ becomes comparable to $v_{\mathrm {e,th} }$ , leading to Landau damping.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] In bounded plasmas, plasma oscillations can still propagate due to fringing fields, even for cold electrons.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] In metals or semiconductors, the ions' periodic potential is accounted for using the effective mass $m^{*}$ .
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Plasma oscillations can result in an effective negative mass.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Consider the mass–spring model in Figure 1.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] As $\omega$ approaches $\omega _{0}$ from above, $m_{\rm {eff}}$ becomes negative.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] This analogy applies to plasmonic systems too (Figure 2).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Near $\omega _{\rm {p}}$ , this effective mass becomes negative.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-oscillation] Metamaterials exploiting this behavior have been studied.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] in a fire pit; fires may produce plasma if hot enough.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The presence of charged particles makes plasma electrically conductive, with the dynamics of individual particles and macroscopic plasma motion governed by collective electromagnetic fields and very sensitive to externally applied fields.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The response of plasma to electromagnetic fields is used in many modern devices and technologies, such as plasma televisions or plasma etching.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Depending on the physical conditions, a certain number of neutral particles may also be present, in which case plasma is called partially ionized.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Neon signs and lightning are examples of partially ionized plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Unlike the phase transitions between the three other classical states of matter, the transition to plasma is not well defined and is a matter of interpretation and context.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Whether a given degree of ionization suffices to call a substance "plasma" depends on the specific phenomenon being considered.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Lewi Tonks and Harold Mott-Smith, both of whom worked with Langmuir in the 1920s, recall that Langmuir first used the term by analogy with the blood plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Mott-Smith recalls, in particular, that the transport of electrons from thermionic filaments reminded Langmuir of "the way blood plasma carries red and white corpuscles and germs." The word 'plasma' in blood plasma ultimately derives from the Greek word for the result of forming or moulding.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma science as derives from Irving Langmuir's work in the 1920s, but the issues and initial understanding derives from history of electricity.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The electric arc was discovered independently by Vasily Petrov and Humphry Davy in 1803.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In 1831, Michael Faraday systematically investigated electric glow discharge in rarefied gases.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Electrical conduction through gases was originally thought to be similar to condition in liquids.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Sir William Crookes, investigating low-pressure discharges, suggested a different model, presenting the idea of a fourth state of matter in a well-known paper in 1879.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma is called the *fourth state of matter* after solid, liquid, and gas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] It is a state of matter in which an ionized substance becomes highly electrically conductive to the point that long-range electric and magnetic fields dominate its behaviour.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma is typically an electrically quasineutral medium of unbound positive and negative particles (i.e., the overall charge of a plasma is roughly zero).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Although these particles are unbound, they are not "free" in the sense of not experiencing forces.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Moving charged particles generate electric currents, and any movement of a charged plasma particle affects and is affected by the fields created by the other charges.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In turn, this governs collective behaviour with many degrees of variation.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma is distinct from the other states of matter.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In particular, describing a low-density plasma as merely an "ionized gas" is wrong and misleading, even though it is similar to the gas phase in that both assume no definite shape or volume.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The strength and range of the electric force and the good conductivity of plasmas usually ensure that the densities of positive and negative charges in any sizeable region are equal ("quasineutrality").
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] A plasma with a significant excess of charge density, or, in the extreme case, is composed of a single species, is called a non-neutral plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In such a plasma, electric fields play a dominant role.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Examples are charged particle beams, an electron cloud in a Penning trap and positron plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] A dusty plasma contains tiny charged particles of dust (typically found in space).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The dust particles acquire high charges and interact with each other.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] A plasma that contains larger particles is called grain plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Under laboratory conditions, dusty plasmas are also called *complex plasmas*.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] For plasma to exist, ionization is necessary.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The term "plasma density" by itself usually refers to the electron density $n_{e}$ , that is, the number of charge-contributing electrons per unit volume.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] where $n_{i}$ is the ion density and $n_{n}$ the neutral density (in number of particles per unit volume).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In the case of fully ionized matter, $\alpha =1$ .
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Because of the quasineutrality of plasma, the electron and ion densities are related by $n_{e}=\langle Z_{i}\rangle n_{i}$ , where $\langle Z_{i}\rangle$ is the average ion charge (in units of the elementary charge).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma temperature, commonly measured in kelvin or electronvolts, is a measure of the thermal kinetic energy per particle.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] High temperatures are usually needed to sustain ionization, which is a defining feature of a plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The degree of plasma ionization is determined by the electron temperature relative to the ionization energy (and more weakly by the density).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In thermal equilibrium, the relationship is given by the Saha equation.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] At low temperatures, ions and electrons tend to recombine into bound states—atoms—and the plasma will eventually become a gas in the absence of other ionization mechanisms.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In most cases, the electrons and heavy plasma particles (ions and neutral atoms) separately have a relatively well-defined temperature; that is, their energy distribution function is close to a Maxwellian even in the presence of strong electric or magnetic fields.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] However, because of the large difference in mass between electrons and ions, their temperatures may be different, sometimes significantly so.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] This is especially common in weakly ionized technological plasmas, where the ions are often near the ambient temperature while electrons reach thousands of kelvin.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The opposite case is the z-pinch plasma where the ion temperature may exceed that of electrons.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Since plasmas are very good electrical conductors, electric potentials play an important role.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The average potential in the space between charged particles, independent of how it can be measured, is called the "plasma potential", or the "space potential".
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] If an electrode is inserted into a plasma, its potential will generally lie considerably below the plasma potential due to what is termed a Debye sheath.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The good electrical conductivity of plasmas makes their electric fields very small.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] This results in the important concept of "quasineutrality", which says the density of negative charges is approximately equal to the density of positive charges over large volumes of the plasma ( $n_{e}=\langle Z\rangle n_{i}$ ), but on the scale of the Debye length, there can be charge imbalance.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In the special case that *double layers* are formed, the charge separation can extend some tens of Debye lengths.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The magnitude of the potentials and electric fields must be determined by means other than simply finding the net charge density.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] It is possible to produce a plasma that is not quasineutral.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] An electron beam, for example, has only negative charges.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The density of a non-neutral plasma must generally be very low, or it must be very small, otherwise, it will be dissipated by the repulsive electrostatic force.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The existence of charged particles causes the plasma to generate, and be affected by, magnetic fields.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma with a magnetic field strong enough to influence the motion of the charged particles is said to be magnetized.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] It is often the case that the electrons are magnetized while the ions are not.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Magnetized plasmas are *anisotropic*, meaning that their properties in the direction parallel to the magnetic field are different from those perpendicular to it.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] To completely describe the state of a plasma, all of the particle locations and velocities that describe the electromagnetic field in the plasma region would need to be written down.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] However, it is generally not practical or necessary to keep track of all the particles in a plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Fluid models describe plasmas in terms of smoothed quantities, like density and averaged velocity around each position (see Plasma parameters).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] One simple fluid model, magnetohydrodynamics, treats the plasma as a single fluid governed by a combination of Maxwell's equations and the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] A more general description is the two-fluid plasma, where the ions and electrons are described separately.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Fluid models are often accurate when collisionality is sufficiently high to keep the plasma velocity distribution close to a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Because fluid models usually describe the plasma in terms of a single flow at a certain temperature at each spatial location, they can neither capture velocity space structures like beams or double layers, nor resolve wave-particle effects.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Kinetic models describe the particle velocity distribution function at each point in the plasma and therefore do not need to assume a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] A kinetic description is often necessary for collisionless plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] There are two common approaches to kinetic description of a plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] One is based on representing the smoothed distribution function on a grid in velocity and position.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The other, known as the particle-in-cell (PIC) technique, includes kinetic information by following the trajectories of a large number of individual particles.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Kinetic models are generally more computationally intensive than fluid models.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The Vlasov equation may be used to describe the dynamics of a system of charged particles interacting with an electromagnetic field.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In magnetized plasmas, a gyrokinetic approach can substantially reduce the computational expense of a fully kinetic simulation.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasmas are studied by the vast academic field of *plasma science* or *plasma physics*, including several sub-disciplines such as space plasma physics.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma constitutes more than 99% of matter observed in the visible universe.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Above the Earth's surface, the ionosphere is a plasma, and the magnetosphere contains plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Within the Solar System, interplanetary space is filled with the plasma expelled via the solar wind, extending from the Sun's surface out to the heliopause.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Furthermore, all the distant stars, and much of interstellar space or intergalactic space is also filled with plasma, albeit at very low densities.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Astrophysical plasmas are also observed in accretion disks around stars or compact objects like white dwarfs, neutron stars, or black holes in close binary star systems.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Plasma is associated with ejection of material in astrophysical jets, which have been observed with accreting black holes or in active galaxies like M87's jet that possibly extends out to 5,000 light-years.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Most artificial plasmas are generated by the application of electric and/or magnetic fields through a gas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Just like the many uses of plasma, there are several means for its generation.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] However, one principle is common to all of them: there must be energy input to produce and sustain it.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] For this case, plasma is generated when an electric current is applied across a dielectric gas or fluid (an electrically non-conducting material) as can be seen in the adjacent image, which shows a discharge tube as a simple example (DC used for simplicity).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The potential difference and subsequent electric field pull the bound electrons (negative) toward the anode (positive electrode) while the cathode (negative electrode) pulls the nucleus.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The underlying process is the Townsend avalanche, where collisions between electrons and neutral gas atoms create more ions and electrons (as can be seen in the figure on the right).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The first impact of an electron on an atom results in one ion and two electrons.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Therefore, the number of charged particles increases rapidly (in the millions) only "after about 20 successive sets of collisions", mainly due to a small mean free path (average distance travelled between collisions).
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Electric arc is a continuous electric discharge between two electrodes, similar to lightning.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] With ample current density, the discharge forms a luminous arc, where the inter-electrode material (usually, a gas) undergoes various stages — saturation, breakdown, glow, transition, and thermal arc.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The voltage rises to its maximum in the saturation stage, and thereafter it undergoes fluctuations of the various stages, while the current progressively increases throughout.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Electrical resistance along the arc creates heat, which dissociates more gas molecules and ionizes the resulting atoms.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Therefore, the electrical energy is given to electrons, which, due to their great mobility and large numbers, are able to disperse it rapidly by elastic collisions to the heavy particles.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] A world effort was triggered in the 1960s to study magnetohydrodynamic converters in order to bring MHD power conversion to market with commercial power plants of a new kind, converting the kinetic energy of a high velocity plasma into electricity with no moving parts at a high efficiency.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Such ionized gases used in "plasma technology" ("technological" or "engineered" plasmas) are usually *weakly ionized gases* in the sense that only a tiny fraction of the gas molecules are ionized.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] These kinds of weakly ionized gases are also nonthermal "cold" plasmas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In the presence of magnetics fields, the study of such magnetized nonthermal weakly ionized gases involves resistive magnetohydrodynamics with low magnetic Reynolds number, a challenging field of plasma physics where calculations require dyadic tensors in a 7-dimensional phase space.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] When used in combination with a high Hall parameter, a critical value triggers the problematic electrothermal instability which limited these technological developments.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Although the underlying equations governing plasmas are relatively simple, plasma behaviour is extraordinarily varied and subtle: the emergence of unexpected behaviour from a simple model is a typical feature of a complex system.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Such systems lie in some sense on the boundary between ordered and disordered behaviour and cannot typically be described either by simple, smooth, mathematical functions, or by pure randomness.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The spontaneous formation of interesting spatial features on a wide range of length scales is one manifestation of plasma complexity.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The features are interesting, for example, because they are very sharp, spatially intermittent (the distance between features is much larger than the features themselves), or have a fractal form.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Many of these features were first studied in the laboratory, and have subsequently been recognized throughout the universe.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Striations or string-like structures are seen in many plasmas, like the plasma ball, the aurora, lightning, electric arcs, solar flares, and supernova remnants.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] They are sometimes associated with larger current densities, and the interaction with the magnetic field can form a magnetic rope structure.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Filamentation also refers to the self-focusing of a high power laser pulse.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] At high powers, the nonlinear part of the index of refraction becomes important and causes a higher index of refraction in the center of the laser beam, where the laser is brighter than at the edges, causing a feedback that focuses the laser even more.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The tighter focused laser has a higher peak brightness (irradiance) that forms a plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The plasma has an index of refraction lower than one, and causes a defocusing of the laser beam.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] The interplay of the focusing index of refraction, and the defocusing plasma makes the formation of a long filament of plasma that can be micrometers to kilometers in length.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] One interesting aspect of the filamentation generated plasma is the relatively low ion density due to defocusing effects of the ionized electrons.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Impermeable plasma is a type of thermal plasma which acts like an impermeable solid with respect to gas or cold plasma and can be physically pushed.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] Interaction of cold gas and thermal plasma was briefly studied by a group led by Hannes Alfvén in 1960s and 1970s for its possible applications in insulation of fusion plasma from the reactor walls.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] However, later it was found that the external magnetic fields in this configuration could induce kink instabilities in the plasma and subsequently lead to an unexpectedly high heat loss to the walls.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] In 2013, a group of materials scientists reported that they have successfully generated stable impermeable plasma with no magnetic confinement using only an ultrahigh-pressure blanket of cold gas.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] While spectroscopic data on the characteristics of plasma were claimed to be difficult to obtain due to the high pressure, the passive effect of plasma on synthesis of different nanostructures clearly suggested the effective confinement.
[src:plasma-physics/plasma-physics] They also showed that upon maintaining the impermeability for a few tens of seconds, screening of ions at the plasma-gas interface could give rise to a strong secondary mode of heating (known as viscous heating) leading to different kinetics of reactions and formation of complex nanomaterials.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] A **tokamak** (/ˈtoʊkəmæk/; Russian: токамáк) is a machine which uses a powerful magnetic field generated by external magnets to confine plasma in the shape of an axially symmetrical torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The tokamak is the leading candidate of magnetic confinement fusion designs being developed to produce controlled thermonuclear fusion power.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Tokamaks use a combination of a central solenoid and toroidal and poloidal magnets to shape a ring of plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This is heated by a range of methods, including neutral-beam injection, electron and ion cyclotron resonance, lower hybrid resonance.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Nuclear fusion may be achieved, measured by neutron detectors.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Due to requiring a continuously changing magnetic field, modern tokamaks sustain "plasma discharges" on the timescales of seconds or minutes.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The world's largest operational tokamak by radius and plasma current is the JT-60SA in Japan.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Other operational experiments include WEST in France and EAST in China.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER) tokamak is the primary global effort to research fusion power, under construction in France, and aimed for completion by 2034.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Many smaller designs, and offshoots like the spherical tokamak, such as at MAST upgrade in UK, continue to be used to investigate performance parameters and other issues.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Commercial fusion companies have also proposed tokamak construction in recent years, including Commonwealth Fusion Systems' SPARC design.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Tokamaks were first conceptualized by Soviet physicists Andrei Sakharov and Igor Tamm.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Experiments were constructed from 1951 at Kurchatov Institute in Moscow led by Lev Artsimovich.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Their 1958 T-1 device is sometimes considered the first tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The same year, the USSR, US, and UK began sharing fusion research.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] A "tokamak stampede" occurred after 1968, when British Culham Laboratory scientists verified high performance results of the Kurchatov Institute's T-3 tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] It had been demonstrated that a stable plasma equilibrium requires magnetic field lines that wind around the torus in a helix shape.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The z-pinch and stellarator concepts of magnetic confinement had attempted this, but demonstrated serious instabilities.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The safety factor (labelled *q* in mathematical notation) guided tokamak development: tokamaks with *q > 1* strongly suppressed these instabilities.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] By the mid-1970s, dozens of tokamaks were in use around the world.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory (PPPL) in the US became another center of research, beginning with the 1975 Princeton Large Torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the late 1970s, the Kurchatov Institute tested the first superconducting magnets and divertors in tokamaks, ubiquitous in modern large designs.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor (TFTR), and the Joint European Torus (JET) were the first to run experiments with an admixture of rare tritium to deuterium, previous reactors demonstrated fusion in a deuterium plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Both reactors developed understanding of alpha particles' role in heating fusion plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] JET also researched the high-confinement mode, and set magnetic confinement fusion power records standing as of 2025, for energy gain factor (*Q* = 0.67), total energy output (69 MJ), and fusion power (16 MW).
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] These machines demonstrated new problems that limited their performance.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Solving these would require a much larger and more expensive machine, beyond the abilities of any one country.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] After an initial agreement between Ronald Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev in November 1985, the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER) project emerged; construction of the complex began in Cadarache, France in 2013, and tokamak assembly began in 2020.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The term "tokamak" was coined in 1957 by Igor Golovin, a student of academician Igor Kurchatov.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Later, this name was borrowed by many languages.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The acronym "токамаг" ends in a г, which normally represents a voiced velar stop [g] in Russian orthography, but in Russian this sound devoices to a voiceless velar stop [k] (otherwise written к) at the end of a word, so both spellings are pronounced identically.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In 1934, Mark Oliphant, Paul Harteck and Ernest Rutherford were the first to achieve fusion on Earth, using a particle accelerator to shoot deuterium nuclei into metal foil containing deuterium or other atoms.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This allowed them to measure the nuclear cross section of various fusion reactions, and determined that the deuterium–deuterium reaction occurred at a lower energy than other reactions, peaking at about 100,000 electronvolts (100 keV).
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Accelerator-based fusion is not practical because the reactor cross section is tiny; most of the particles in the accelerator will scatter off the fuel, not fuse with it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] These scatterings cause the particles to lose energy to the point where they can no longer undergo fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The energy put into these particles is thus lost, and it is easy to demonstrate this is much more energy than the resulting fusion reactions can release.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] To maintain fusion and produce net energy output, the bulk of the fuel must be raised to high temperatures so its atoms are constantly colliding at high speed; this gives rise to the name *thermonuclear* due to the high temperatures needed to bring it about.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During the Manhattan Project, the first practical way to reach these temperatures was created, using an atomic bomb.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In 1944, Fermi gave a talk on the physics of fusion in the context of a then-hypothetical hydrogen bomb.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] However, some thought had already been given to *controlled* fusion, and James L.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Tuck and Stanislaw Ulam had attempted such using shaped charges driving a metal foil infused with deuterium, although without success.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The first attempts to build a practical fusion machine took place in the United Kingdom, where George Paget Thomson had selected the pinch effect as a promising technique in 1945.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] After several failed attempts to gain funding, he gave up and asked two graduate students, Stanley (Stan) W.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Cousins and Alan Alfred Ware (1924–2010), to build something out of surplus radar equipment.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This successfully operated in 1948, but showed no clear evidence of fusion and failed to gain the interest of the Atomic Energy Research Establishment.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In 1950, Oleg Lavrentiev, then a Soviet Army sergeant stationed on Sakhalin, wrote a letter to the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The letter outlined the idea of using an atomic bomb to ignite fusion fuel, and then went on to describe a system that used electrostatic fields to contain hot plasma in a steady state for energy production.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The letter was sent to Andrei Sakharov for comment.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When heated to fusion temperatures, the electrons in atoms dissociate, resulting in a fluid of nuclei and electrons known as plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Unlike electrically neutral atoms, a plasma is electrically conductive, and can, therefore, be manipulated by electrical or magnetic fields.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Sakharov's concern about the electrodes led him to consider using magnetic confinement instead of electrostatic.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the case of a magnetic field, the particles will circle around the lines of force.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] As the particles are moving at high speed, their resulting paths look like a helix.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] If one arranges a magnetic field so lines of force are parallel and close together, the particles orbiting adjacent lines may collide, and fuse.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Such a field can be created in a solenoid, a cylinder with magnets wrapped around the outside.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The combined fields of the magnets create a set of parallel magnetic lines running down the length of the cylinder.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This arrangement prevents the particles from moving sideways to the wall of the cylinder, but it does not prevent them from running out the end.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The obvious solution to this problem is to bend the cylinder around into a donut shape, or torus, so that the lines form a series of continual rings.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In this arrangement, the particles circle endlessly.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Sakharov discussed the concept with Igor Tamm, and by the end of October 1950 the two had written a proposal and sent it to Igor Kurchatov, the director of the atomic bomb project within the USSR, and his deputy, Igor Golovin.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] However, this initial proposal ignored a fundamental problem; when arranged along a straight solenoid, the external magnets are evenly spaced, but when bent around into a torus, they are closer together on the inside of the ring than the outside.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This leads to uneven forces that cause the particles to drift away from their magnetic lines.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During visits to the Laboratory of Measuring Instruments of the USSR Academy of Sciences (LIPAN), the Soviet nuclear research centre, Sakharov suggested two possible solutions to this problem.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] One was to suspend a current-carrying ring in the centre of the torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The current in the ring would produce a magnetic field that would mix with the one from the magnets on the outside.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The resulting field would be twisted into a helix, so that any given particle would find itself repeatedly on the outside, then inside, of the torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The drifts caused by the uneven fields are in opposite directions on the inside and outside, so over the course of multiple orbits around the long axis of the torus, the opposite drifts would cancel out.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Alternately, he suggested using an external magnet to induce a current in the plasma itself, instead of a separate metal ring, which would have the same effect.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In January 1951, Kurchatov arranged a meeting at LIPAN to consider Sakharov's concepts.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] They found widespread interest and support, and in February a report on the topic was forwarded to Lavrentiy Beria, who oversaw the atomic efforts in the USSR.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] On 25 March 1951, Argentine President Juan Perón announced that a former German scientist, Ronald Richter, had succeeded in producing fusion at a laboratory scale as part of what is now known as the Huemul Project.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Scientists around the world were excited by the announcement, but soon concluded it was not true; simple calculations showed that his experimental setup could not produce enough energy to heat the fusion fuel to the needed temperatures.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Although dismissed by nuclear researchers, the widespread news coverage meant politicians were suddenly aware of, and receptive to, fusion research.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the UK, Thomson was suddenly granted considerable funding.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Over the next months, two projects based on the pinch system were up and running.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the US, Lyman Spitzer read the Huemul story, realized it was false, and set about designing a machine that would work.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In May 1951, he was awarded $50,000 to begin research on his stellarator concept.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Jim Tuck had returned to the UK briefly and saw Thomson's pinch machines.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When he returned to Los Alamos he also received $50,000 directly from the Los Alamos budget.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In mid-April 1951, Dmitri Efremov of the Scientific Research Institute of Electrophysical Apparatus stormed into Kurchatov's study with a magazine containing a story about Richter's work, demanding to know why they were beaten by the Argentines.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Kurchatov immediately contacted Beria with a proposal to set up a separate fusion research laboratory with Lev Artsimovich as director.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Only days later, on 5 May 1951, the proposal had been signed by Joseph Stalin.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] By October 1951, Sakharov and Tamm had completed a far more detailed consideration of their original proposal, calling for something with a major radius (of the torus as a whole) of 12 metres (39 ft) and a minor radius (the interior of the cylinder) of 2 metres (6 ft 7 in).
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The proposal suggested the system could produce 100 grams (3.5 oz) of tritium a day, or breed 10 kilograms (22 lb) of U233 a day.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] As the idea was further developed, it was realized that a current in the plasma could create a field that was strong enough to confine the plasma as well, removing the need for the external coils.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At this point, the Soviet researchers had re-invented the pinch system being developed in the UK, although they had come to this design from a very different starting point.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Once the idea of using the pinch effect for confinement had been proposed, a much simpler solution became evident.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Instead of a large toroid, one could simply induce the current into a linear tube, which could cause the plasma within to collapse down into a filament.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This had a huge advantage; the current in the plasma would heat it through normal resistive heating, but this would not heat the plasma to fusion temperatures.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] However, as the plasma collapsed, the adiabatic process would result in the temperature rising dramatically, more than enough for fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] With this development, only Golovin and Natan Yavlinsky continued considering the more static toroidal arrangement.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] On 4 July 1952, Nikolai Filippov's group measured neutrons being released from a linear pinch machine.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Lev Artsimovich demanded that they check everything before concluding fusion had occurred, and during these checks, they found that the neutrons were not from fusion at all.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This same linear arrangement had also occurred to researchers in the UK and US, and their machines showed the same behaviour.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] But the great secrecy surrounding the type of research meant that none of the groups were aware that others were also working on it, let alone having the identical problem.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] After much study, it was found that some of the released neutrons were produced by instabilities in the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] There were two common types of instability, the *sausage* that was seen primarily in linear machines, and the *kink* which was most common in the toroidal machines.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Groups in all three countries began studying the formation of these instabilities and potential ways to address them.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Important contributions to the field were made by Martin David Kruskal and Martin Schwarzschild in the US, and Shafranov in the USSR.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] One idea that came from these studies became known as the "stabilized pinch".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This concept added additional coils to the outside of the chamber, which created a magnetic field that would be present in the plasma before the pinch discharge.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In most concepts, the externally induced field was relatively weak, and because a plasma is diamagnetic, it penetrated only the outer areas of the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When the pinch discharge occurred and the plasma quickly contracted, this field became "frozen in" to the resulting filament, creating a strong field in its outer layers.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the US, this was known as "giving the plasma a backbone".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Sakharov revisited his original toroidal concepts and came to a slightly different conclusion about how to stabilize the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The layout would be the same as the stabilized pinch concept, but the role of the two fields would be reversed.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In 1955, with the linear approaches still subject to instability, the first toroidal device was built in the USSR.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] TMP was a classic pinch machine, similar to models in the UK and US of the same era.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The vacuum chamber was made of ceramic, and the spectra of the discharges showed silica, meaning the plasma was not perfectly confined by magnetic field and hitting the walls of the chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Two smaller machines followed, using copper shells.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The conductive shells were intended to help stabilize the plasma, but were not completely successful in any of the machines that tried it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] With progress apparently stalled, in 1955, Kurchatov called an All Union conference of Soviet researchers with the ultimate aim of opening up fusion research within the USSR.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In April 1956, Kurchatov travelled to the UK as part of a widely publicized visit by Nikita Khrushchev and Nikolai Bulganin.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] He offered to give a talk at Atomic Energy Research Establishment, at the former RAF Harwell, where he shocked the hosts by presenting a detailed historical overview of the Soviet fusion efforts.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] He took time to note, in particular, the neutrons seen in early machines and warned that neutrons did not mean fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Unknown to Kurchatov, the British ZETA stabilized pinch machine was being built at the far end of the former runway.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] ZETA was, by far, the largest and most powerful fusion machine to date.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Supported by experiments on earlier designs that had been modified to include stabilization, ZETA intended to produce low levels of fusion reactions.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This was apparently a great success, and in January 1958, they announced the fusion had been achieved in ZETA based on the release of neutrons and measurements of the plasma temperature.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Vitaly Shafranov and Stanislav Braginskii examined the news reports and attempted to figure out how it worked.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] One possibility they considered was the use of weak "frozen in" fields, but rejected this, believing the fields would not last long enough.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] They then concluded ZETA was essentially identical to the devices they had been studying, with strong external fields.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] By this time, Soviet researchers had decided to build a larger toroidal machine along the lines suggested by Sakharov.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Today this basic concept is known as the *safety factor*.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The ratio of the number of times the particle orbits the major axis compared to the minor axis is denoted *q*, and the *Kruskal-Shafranov Limit* stated that the kink will be suppressed as long as *q* > 1.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This path is controlled by the relative strengths of the externally induced magnetic field compared to the field created by the internal current.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] To have *q* > 1, the external magnets must be much more powerful, or alternatively, the internal current has to be reduced.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Following this criterion, design began on a new reactor, T-1, which today is known as the first real tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] T-1 used both stronger external magnetic fields and a reduced current compared to stabilized pinch machines like ZETA.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The success of the T-1 resulted in its recognition as the first working tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] For his work on "powerful impulse discharges in a gas, to obtain unusually high temperatures needed for thermonuclear processes", Yavlinskii was awarded the Lenin Prize and the Stalin Prize in 1958.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Yavlinskii was already preparing the design of an even larger model, later built as T-3.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] With the apparently successful ZETA announcement, Yavlinskii's concept was viewed very favourably.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Details of ZETA became public in a series of articles in *Nature* later in January.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] To Shafranov's surprise, the system did use the "frozen in" field concept.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] He remained sceptical, but a team at the Ioffe Institute in St.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Petersburg began plans to build a similar machine known as Alpha.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Only a few months later, in May, the ZETA team issued a release stating they had not achieved fusion, and that they had been misled by erroneous measures of the plasma temperature.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] It demonstrated very high energy losses through radiation.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This was traced to impurities in the plasma due to the vacuum system causing outgassing from the container materials.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In order to explore solutions to this problem, another small device was constructed, T-2.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This used an internal liner of corrugated metal that was baked at 550 °C (1,022 °F) to cook off trapped gasses.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] As part of the second Atoms for Peace meeting in Geneva in September 1958, the Soviet delegation released many papers covering their fusion research.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Among them was a set of initial results on their toroidal machines, which at that point had shown nothing of note.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The "star" of the show was a large model of Spitzer's stellarator, which immediately caught the attention of the Soviets.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Kurchatov began asking Yavlinskii to change their T-3 design to a stellarator, but they convinced him that the current provided a useful second role in heating, something the stellarator lacked.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At the time of the show, the stellarator had suffered a long string of minor problems that were just being solved.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Solving these revealed that the diffusion rate of the plasma was much faster than theory predicted.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Similar problems were seen in all the contemporary designs, for one reason or another.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The stellarator, various pinch concepts and the magnetic mirror machines in both the US and USSR all demonstrated problems that limited their confinement times.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] From the first studies of controlled fusion, there was a problem lurking in the background.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During the Manhattan Project, David Bohm had been part of the team working on isotopic separation of uranium.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the post-war era he continued working with plasmas in magnetic fields.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Using basic theory, one would expect the plasma to diffuse across the lines of force at a rate inversely proportional to the square of the strength of the field, meaning that small increases in force would greatly improve confinement.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] But based on their experiments, Bohm developed an empirical formula, now known as Bohm diffusion, that suggested the rate was linear with the magnetic force, not its square.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] If Bohm's formula was correct, there was no hope one could build a fusion reactor based on magnetic confinement.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] To confine the plasma at the temperatures needed for fusion, the magnetic field would have to be orders of magnitude greater than any known magnet.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Spitzer ascribed the difference between the Bohm and classical diffusion rates to turbulence in the plasma, and believed the steady fields of the stellarator would not suffer from this problem.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Various experiments at that time suggested the Bohm rate did not apply, and that the classical formula was correct.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] But by the early 1960s, with all of the various designs leaking plasma at a prodigious rate, Spitzer himself concluded that the Bohm scaling was an inherent quality of plasmas, and that magnetic confinement would not work.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The entire field descended into what became known as "the doldrums", a period of intense pessimism.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In contrast to the other designs, the experimental tokamaks appeared to be progressing well, so well that a minor theoretical problem was now a real concern.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the presence of gravity, there is a small pressure gradient in the plasma, formerly small enough to ignore but now becoming something that had to be addressed.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This led to the addition of yet another set of coils in 1962, which produced a vertical magnetic field that offset these effects.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] These were a success, and by the mid-1960s the machines began to show signs that they were beating the Bohm limit.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At the 1965 Second International Atomic Energy Agency Conference on fusion at the UK's newly opened Culham Centre for Fusion Energy, Artsimovich reported that their systems were surpassing the Bohm limit by 10 times.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Spitzer, reviewing the presentations, suggested that the Bohm limit may still apply; the results were within the range of experimental error of results seen on the stellarators, and the temperature measurements, based on the magnetic fields, were simply not trustworthy.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The next major international fusion meeting was held in August 1968 in Novosibirsk.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] By this time two additional tokamak designs had been completed, TM-2 in 1965, and T-4 in 1968.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Results from T-3 had continued to improve, and similar results were coming from early tests of the new reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At the meeting, the Soviet delegation announced that T-3 was producing electron temperatures of 1000 eV (equivalent to 10 million degrees Celsius) and that confinement time was at least 50 times the Bohm limit.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] These results were at least 10 times that of any other machine.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] If correct, they represented an enormous leap for the fusion community.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Spitzer remained skeptical, noting that the temperature measurements were still based on the indirect calculations from the magnetic properties of the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Many concluded they were due to an effect known as runaway electrons, and that the Soviets were measuring only those extremely energetic electrons and not the bulk temperature.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The Soviets countered with several arguments suggesting the temperature they were measuring was Maxwellian, and the debate raged.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the aftermath of ZETA, the UK teams began the development of new plasma diagnostic tools to provide more accurate measurements.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Among these was the use of a laser to directly measure the temperature of the bulk electrons using Thomson scattering.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This technique was well known and respected in the fusion community; Artsimovich had publicly called it "brilliant".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Artsimovich invited Bas Pease, the head of Culham, to use their devices on the Soviet reactors.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At the height of the Cold War, in what is still considered a major political manoeuvre on Artsimovich's part, British physicists were allowed to visit the Kurchatov Institute, the heart of the Soviet nuclear bomb effort.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The British team, nicknamed "The Culham Five", arrived late in 1968.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] After a lengthy installation and calibration process, the team measured the temperatures over a period of many experimental runs.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Initial results were available by August 1969; the Soviets were correct, their results were accurate.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The team phoned the results home to Culham, who then passed them along in a confidential phone call to Washington.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The final results were published in *Nature* in November 1969.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The results of this announcement have been described as a "veritable stampede" of tokamak construction around the world.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Because the electrical current in the plasma was much lower and produced much less compression than a pinch machine, this meant the temperature of the plasma was limited to the resistive heating rate of the current.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] First proposed in 1950, Spitzer resistivity stated that the electrical resistance of a plasma was reduced as the temperature increased, meaning the heating rate of the plasma would slow as the devices improved and temperatures were pressed higher.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Calculations demonstrated that the resulting maximum temperatures while staying within *q* > 1 would be limited to the low millions of degrees.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Artsimovich had been quick to point this out in Novosibirsk, stating that future progress would require new heating methods to be developed.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] One of the people attending the Novosibirsk meeting in 1968 was Amasa Stone Bishop, one of the leaders of the US fusion program.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] One of the few other devices to show clear evidence of beating the Bohm limit at that time was the multipole concept.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Both Lawrence Livermore and the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory (PPPL), home of Spitzer's stellarator, were building variations on the multipole design.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] While moderately successful on their own, T-3 greatly outperformed either machine.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Bishop was concerned that the multipoles were redundant and thought the US should consider a tokamak of its own.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When he raised the issue at a December 1968 meeting, directors of the labs refused to consider it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Gottlieb of Princeton was exasperated, asking "Do you think that this committee can out-think the scientists?" With the major labs demanding they control their own research, one lab found itself left out.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Oak Ridge had originally entered the fusion field with studies for reactor fueling systems, but branched out into a mirror program of their own.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] By the mid-1960s, their DCX designs were running out of ideas, offering nothing that the similar program at the more prestigious and politically powerful Livermore did not.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This made them highly receptive to new concepts.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] After a considerable internal debate, Herman Postma formed a small group in early 1969 to consider the tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] They came up with a new design, later christened Ormak, that had several novel features.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Primary among them was the way the external field was created in a single large copper block, fed power from a large transformer below the torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This was as opposed to traditional designs that used electric current windings on the outside.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] They felt the single block would produce a much more uniform field.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] It would also have the advantage of allowing the torus to have a smaller major radius, lacking the need to route cables through the donut hole, leading to a lower *aspect ratio*, which the Soviets had already suggested would produce better results.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In early 1969, Artsimovich visited MIT, where he was hounded by those interested in fusion.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] He finally agreed to give several lectures in April and then allowed lengthy question-and-answer sessions.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] As these went on, MIT itself grew interested in the tokamak, having previously stayed out of the fusion field for a variety of reasons.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Bruno Coppi was at MIT at the time, and following the same concepts as Postma's team, came up with his own low-aspect-ratio concept, Alcator.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Instead of Ormak's toroidal transformer, Alcator used traditional ring-shaped magnetic field coils but required them to be much smaller than existing designs.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] MIT's Francis Bitter Magnet Laboratory was the world leader in magnet design and they were confident they could build them.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During 1969, two additional groups entered the field.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At General Atomics, Tihiro Ohkawa had been developing multipole reactors, and submitted a concept based on these ideas.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This was a tokamak that would have a non-circular plasma cross-section; the same math that suggested a lower aspect-ratio would improve performance also suggested that a C or D-shaped plasma would do the same.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Meanwhile, a group at University of Texas at Austin was proposing a relatively simple tokamak to explore heating the plasma through deliberately induced turbulence, the Texas Turbulent Tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When the members of the Atomic Energy Commissions' Fusion Steering Committee met again in June 1969, they had "tokamak proposals coming out of our ears".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The only major lab working on a toroidal design that was not proposing a tokamak was Princeton, who refused to consider it in spite of their Model C stellarator being just about perfect for such a conversion.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] They continued to offer a long list of reasons why the Model C should not be converted.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When these were questioned, a furious debate broke out about whether the Soviet results were reliable.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Watching the debate take place, Gottlieb had a change of heart.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] There was no point moving forward with the tokamak if the Soviet electron temperature measurements were not accurate, so he formulated a plan to either prove or disprove their results.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] While swimming in the pool during the lunch break, he told Harold Furth his plan, to which Furth replied: "well, maybe you're right." After lunch, the various teams presented their designs, at which point Gottlieb presented his idea for a "stellarator-tokamak" based on the Model C.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The Standing Committee noted that this system could be complete in six months, while Ormak would take a year.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] It was only a short time later that the confidential results from the Culham Five were released.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] When they met again in October, the Standing Committee released funding for all of these proposals.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The Model C's new configuration, soon named Symmetrical Tokamak, intended to simply verify the Soviet results, while the others would explore ways to go well beyond T-3.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Experiments on the Symmetric Tokamak began in May 1970, and by early the next year they had confirmed the Soviet results and then surpassed them.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The stellarator was abandoned, and PPPL turned its considerable expertise to the problem of heating the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] PPPL proposed using magnetic compression, a pinch-like technique to compress a warm plasma to raise its temperature, but providing that compression through magnets rather than current.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Oak Ridge suggested neutral beam injection, small particle accelerators that would shoot fuel atoms through the surrounding magnetic field where they would collide with the plasma and heat it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] PPPL's Adiabatic Toroidal Compressor (ATC) began operation in May 1972, followed shortly thereafter by a neutral-beam equipped Ormak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Both demonstrated significant problems, but PPPL leapt past Oak Ridge by fitting beam injectors to ATC and provided clear evidence of successful heating in 1973.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This success "scooped" Oak Ridge, who fell from favour within the Washington Steering Committee.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] By this time a much larger design based on beam heating was under construction, the Princeton Large Torus, or PLT.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] PLT was designed specifically to "give a clear indication whether the tokamak concept plus auxiliary heating can form a basis for a future fusion reactor".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] PLT was an enormous success, continually raising its internal temperature until it hit 60 million Celsius (8,000 eV, eight times T-3's record) in 1978.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This is a key point in the development of the tokamak; fusion reactions become self-sustaining at temperatures between 50 and 100 million Celsius, PLT demonstrated that this was technically achievable.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] These experiments, especially PLT, put the US far in the lead in tokamak research.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This is due largely to budget; a tokamak cost about $500,000 and the US annual fusion budget was around $25 million at that time.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] They could afford to explore all of the promising methods of heating, ultimately discovering neutral beams to be among the most effective.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During this period, Robert Hirsch took over the Directorate of fusion development in the U.S.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Hirsch felt that the program could not be sustained at its current funding levels without demonstrating tangible results.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] He began to reformulate the entire program.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] What had once been a lab-led effort of mostly scientific exploration was now a Washington-led effort to build a working power-producing reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This was given a boost by the 1973 oil crisis, which led to greatly increased research into alternative energy systems.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] It appeared all that was needed to build a power-producing reactor was to put all of these design concepts into a single machine, one that would be capable of running with the radioactive tritium in its fuel mix.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During the 1970s, four major second-generation proposals were funded worldwide.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The Soviets continued their development lineage with the T-15, while a pan-European effort was developing the Joint European Torus (JET) and Japan began the JT-60 effort (originally known as the "Breakeven Plasma Test Facility").
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] In the US, Hirsch began formulating plans for a similar design, skipping over proposals for another stepping-stone design directly to a tritium-burning one.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This emerged as the Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor (TFTR), run directly from Washington and not linked to any specific lab.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Originally favouring Oak Ridge as the host, Hirsch moved it to PPPL after others convinced him they would work the hardest on it because they had the most to lose.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The excitement was so widespread that several commercial ventures to produce commercial tokamaks began around this time.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Best known among these, in 1978, Bob Guccione, publisher of Penthouse Magazine, met Robert Bussard and became the world's biggest and most committed private investor in fusion technology, ultimately putting $20 million of his own money into Bussard's Compact Tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Funding by the Riggs Bank led to this effort being known as the Riggatron.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] TFTR won the construction race and began operation in 1982, followed shortly by JET in 1983 and JT-60 in 1985.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] JET quickly took the lead in critical experiments, moving from test gases to deuterium and increasingly powerful "shots".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] But it soon became clear that none of the new systems were working as expected.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] A host of new instabilities appeared, along with a number of more practical problems that continued to interfere with their performance.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] On top of this, dangerous "excursions" of the plasma hitting with the walls of the reactor were evident in both TFTR and JET.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Even when working perfectly, plasma confinement at fusion temperatures, the so-called "fusion triple product" continued to be far below what would be needed for a practical reactor design.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Through the mid-1980s the reasons for many of these problems became clear, and various solutions were offered.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] However, these would significantly increase the size and complexity of the machines.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] A follow-on design incorporating these changes would be both enormous and vastly more expensive than either JET or TFTR.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] A new period of pessimism descended on the fusion field.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] At the same time these experiments were demonstrating problems, much of the impetus for the US's massive funding disappeared; in 1986 Ronald Reagan declared the 1970s energy crisis was over, and funding for advanced energy sources had been slashed in the early 1980s.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Some thought of an international reactor design had been ongoing since June 1973 under the name INTOR, for INternational TOkamak Reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] This was originally started through an agreement between Richard Nixon and Leonid Brezhnev, but had been moving slowly since its first real meeting on 23 November 1978.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] During the Geneva Summit in November 1985, Reagan raised the issue with Mikhail Gorbachev and proposed reforming the organization.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The next year, an agreement was signed between the US, Soviet Union, European Union and Japan, creating the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor organization.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Design work began in 1988, and since that time the ITER reactor has been the primary tokamak design effort worldwide.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] Stronger field magnets enable high energy gain in a much smaller tokamak; concepts such as FIRE, IGNITOR, and the Compact Ignition Tokamak (CIT) were early proposals.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The commercial availability of high temperature superconductors (HTS) in the 2010s opened a promising pathway to building the higher field magnets required to achieve ITER-like levels of energy gain in a compact device.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] British startup Tokamak Energy is planning on building a net-energy spherical tokamak using HTS magnets.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p01] The joint EU/Japan JT-60SA reactor achieved first plasma on October 23, 2023, after a two-year delay caused by an electrical short.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Positively charged ions and negatively charged electrons in a fusion plasma are at very high temperatures, and have correspondingly large velocities.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In order to maintain the fusion process, particles from the hot plasma must be confined in the central region, or the plasma will rapidly cool.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Magnetic confinement fusion devices exploit the fact that charged particles in a magnetic field experience a Lorentz force and follow helical paths along the field lines.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The simplest magnetic confinement system is a solenoid.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] A plasma in a solenoid will spiral about the lines of field running down its center, preventing motion towards the sides.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] However, this does not prevent motion towards the ends.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The obvious solution is to bend the solenoid around into a circle, forming a torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] However, it was demonstrated that such an arrangement is not uniform; for purely geometric reasons, the field on the outside edge of the torus is lower than on the inside edge.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This asymmetry causes the electrons and ions to drift across the field, and eventually hit the walls of the torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The solution is to shape the lines so they do not simply run around the torus, but twist around like the stripes on a barber pole or candycane.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In such a field any single particle will find itself at the outside edge where it will drift one way, then as it follows its magnetic line around the torus it will find itself on the inside edge, where it will drift the other way.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This cancellation is not perfect, but calculations showed it was enough to allow the fuel to remain in the reactor for a useful time.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The two first solutions to making a design with the required twist were the stellarator which did so through a mechanical arrangement, twisting the entire torus, and the z-pinch design which ran an electrical current through the plasma to create a second magnetic field to the same end.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Both demonstrated improved confinement times compared to a simple torus, but both also demonstrated a variety of effects that caused the plasma to be lost from the reactors at rates that were not sustainable.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The tokamak is essentially identical to the z-pinch concept in its physical layout.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Its key innovation was the realization that the instabilities that were causing the pinch to lose its plasma could be controlled.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The issue was how "twisty" the fields were; fields that caused the particles to transit inside and out more than once per orbit around the long axis torus were much more stable than devices that had less twist.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This ratio of twists to orbits became known as the *safety factor*, denoted *q*.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Previous devices operated at *q* about 1⁄3, while the tokamak operates at *q* ≫ 1.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This increases stability by orders of magnitude.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When the problem is considered even more closely, the need for a vertical (parallel to the axis of rotation) component of the magnetic field arises.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The Lorentz force of the toroidal plasma current in the vertical field provides the inward force that holds the plasma torus in equilibrium.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] While the tokamak addresses the issue of plasma stability in a gross sense, plasmas are also subject to a number of dynamic instabilities.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] One of these, the kink instability, is strongly suppressed by the tokamak layout, a side-effect of the high safety factors of tokamaks.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The lack of kinks allowed the tokamak to operate at much higher temperatures than previous machines, and this allowed a host of new phenomena to appear.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] One of these, the banana orbits, is caused by the wide range of particle energies in a tokamak – much of the fuel is hot, but a certain percentage is much cooler.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Due to the high twist of the fields in the tokamak, particles following their lines of force rapidly move towards the inner edge and then outer.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] As they move inward they are subject to increasing magnetic fields due to the smaller radius concentrating the field.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The low-energy particles in the fuel will reflect off this increasing field and begin to travel backwards through the fuel, colliding with the higher energy nuclei and scattering them out of the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This process causes fuel to be lost from the reactor, although this process is slow enough that a practical reactor is still well within reach.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Another instability is tearing instability.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In 2024 researchers used reinforcement learning against a multimodal dynamic model to measure and forecast such instabilities based on signals from multiple diagnostics and actuators at 25 millisecond intervals.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This forecast was used to reduce tearing instabilities in DIII-D6, in the US.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The reward function balanced the conflicting objectives of maximum plasma pressure and instability risks.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In particular, the plasma actively tracked the stable path while maintaining H-mode performance.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] One of the first goals for any controlled fusion device is to reach *breakeven*, the point where the energy being released by the fusion reactions is equal to the amount of energy being used to maintain the reaction.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The ratio of output to input energy is denoted *Q*, and breakeven corresponds to a *Q* of 1.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] A *Q* of more than one is needed for the reactor to generate net energy, but for practical reasons, it is desirable for it to be much higher.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Once breakeven is reached, further improvements in confinement generally lead to a rapidly increasing *Q*.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] That is because some of the energy being given off by the fusion reactions of the most common fusion fuel, a 50-50 mix of deuterium and tritium, is in the form of alpha particles.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] These can collide with the fuel nuclei in the plasma and heat it, reducing the amount of external heat needed.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] At some point, known as *ignition*, this internal self-heating is enough to keep the reaction going without any external heating, corresponding to an infinite *Q*.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In the case of the tokamak, this self-heating process is maximized if the alpha particles remain in the fuel long enough to guarantee they will collide with the fuel.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] As the alphas are electrically charged, they are subject to the same fields that are confining the fuel plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The amount of time they spend in the fuel can be maximized by ensuring their orbit in the field remains within the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] It can be demonstrated that this occurs when the electrical current in the plasma is about 3 MA.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In the early 1970s, studies at Princeton into the use of high-power superconducting magnets in future tokamak designs examined the layout of the magnets.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] They noticed that the arrangement of the main toroidal coils meant that there was significantly more tension between the magnets on the inside of the curvature where they were closer together.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Considering this, they noted that the tensional forces within the magnets would be evened out if they were shaped like a D, rather than an O.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This became known as the "Princeton D-coil".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This was not the first time this sort of arrangement had been considered, although for entirely different reasons.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The safety factor varies across the axis of the machine; for purely geometrical reasons, it is always smaller at the inside edge of the plasma closest to the machine's center because the long axis is shorter there.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] That means that a machine with an average *q* = 2 might still be less than 1 in certain areas.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In the 1970s, it was suggested that one way to counteract this and produce a design with a higher average *q* would be to shape the magnetic fields so that the plasma only filled the outer half of the torus, shaped like a D or C when viewed end-on, instead of the normal circular cross section.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] One of the first machines to incorporate a D-shaped plasma was the JET, which began its design work in 1973.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This decision was made both for theoretical reasons as well as practical; because the force is larger on the inside edge of the torus, there is a large net force pressing inward on the entire reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The D-shape also had the advantage of reducing the net force, as well as making the supported inside edge flatter so it was easier to support.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Code exploring the general layout noticed that a non-circular shape would slowly drift vertically, which led to the addition of an active feedback system to hold it in the center.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Once JET had selected this layout, the General Atomics Doublet III team redesigned that machine into the D-IIID with a D-shaped cross-section, and it was selected for the Japanese JT-60 design as well.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This layout has been largely universal since then.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] One problem seen in all fusion reactors is that the presence of heavier elements causes energy to be lost at an increased rate, cooling the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] During the very earliest development of fusion power, a solution to this problem was found, the *divertor*, essentially a large mass spectrometer that would cause the heavier elements to be flung out of the reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This was initially part of the stellarator designs, where it is easy to integrate into the magnetic windings.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] However, designing a divertor for a tokamak proved to be a very difficult design problem.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Another problem seen in all fusion designs is the heat load that the plasma places on the wall of the confinement vessel.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] There are materials that can handle this load, but they are generally undesirable and expensive heavy metals.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When such materials are sputtered in collisions with hot ions, their atoms mix with the fuel and rapidly cool it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] A solution used on most tokamak designs is the *limiter*, a small ring of light metal that projected into the chamber so that the plasma would hit it before hitting the walls.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This eroded the limiter and caused its atoms to mix with the fuel, but these lighter materials cause less disruption than the wall materials.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When reactors moved to the D-shaped plasmas it was quickly noted that the escaping particle flux of the plasma could be shaped as well.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Over time, this led to the idea of using the fields to create an internal divertor that flings the heavier elements out of the fuel, typically towards the bottom of the reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] There, a pool of liquid lithium metal is used as a sort of limiter; the particles hit it and are rapidly cooled, remaining in the lithium.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This internal pool is much easier to cool, due to its location, and although some lithium atoms are released into the plasma, its very low mass makes it a much smaller problem than even the lightest metals used previously.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] As machines began to explore this newly shaped plasma, they noticed that certain arrangements of the fields and plasma parameters would sometimes enter what is now known as the high-confinement mode, or H-mode, which operated stably at higher temperatures and pressures.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Operating in the H-mode, which can also be seen in stellarators, is now a major design goal of the tokamak design.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Finally, it was noted that when the plasma had a non-uniform density it would give rise to internal electrical currents.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This is known as the *bootstrap current*.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This allows a properly designed reactor to generate some of the internal current needed to twist the magnetic field lines without having to supply it from an external source.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This has a number of advantages, and modern designs all attempt to generate as much of their total current through the bootstrap process as possible.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] By the early 1990s, the combination of these features and others collectively gave rise to the "advanced tokamak" concept.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This forms the basis of modern research, including ITER.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Tokamaks are subject to events known as "disruptions" that cause confinement to be lost in milliseconds.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The two primary mechanisms are the "vertical displacement event" (VDE), in which the entire plasma moves vertically until it touches the upper or lower section of the vacuum chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] By contrast, in the "major disruption", long wavelength, non-axisymmetric magnetohydrodynamical instabilities cause the plasma to be forced into non-symmetrical shapes, often squeezed into the top and bottom of the chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When the plasma touches the vessel walls it undergoes rapid cooling, or "thermal quenching".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In the major disruption case, this is normally accompanied by a brief increase in plasma current as the plasma concentrates.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Quenching ultimately breaks up the plasma confinement.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In the case of the major disruption the current drops again, the "current quench".
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The initial increase in current is not seen in the VDE, and the thermal and current quench occurs at the same time.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In both cases, the thermal and electrical load of the plasma is rapidly deposited on the reactor vessel, which has to be able to handle these loads.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] ITER is designed to handle 2600 of these events over its lifetime.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] For high-energy devices such as ITER, which achieves plasma currents on the order of 15 megaamperes, it is possible the brief increase in current during a major disruption will cross a critical threshold.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This occurs when the current produces a force on the electrons that is higher than the frictional forces of the collisions between particles in the plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In this event, electrons can be accelerated to relativistic velocities, creating so-called "runaway electrons" in the relativistic runaway electron avalanche.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] These retain their energy even during the current quench.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When confinement breaks down, these runaway electrons impact the side of the reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] These can reach 12 megaamps of current deposited in a small area, well beyond the capabilities of any mechanical solution.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In one famous case, the Tokamak de Fontenay aux Roses had a major disruption where the runaway electrons burned a hole through the vacuum chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Major disruptions in tokamaks occur frequently, on the order of a few percent of shots.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The damage is often large but rarely dramatic.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In ITER it is expected that major disruptions would damage the chamber with no possibility to restore the device.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The development of systems to counter the effects of runaway electrons is considered a must-have technology for ITER.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] A large amplitude of the central current density can also result in internal disruptions, or sawteeth, which do not generally terminate the discharge.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Densities over the Greenwald limit, a bound depending on the plasma current and the minor radius, typically leads to disruptions.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] While it has been exceeded up to factors of 10, it remains an important concept describing the phenomenology of the transition of the plasma flow, which still needs to be understood.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In an operating fusion reactor, part of the energy generated will serve to maintain the plasma temperature as fresh deuterium and tritium are introduced.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] However, in the startup of a reactor, either initially or after a temporary shutdown, the plasma will have to be heated to its operating temperature of greater than 10 keV (over 100 million degrees Celsius).
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In current tokamak (and other) magnetic fusion experiments, insufficient fusion energy is produced to maintain the plasma temperature, and constant external heating must be supplied.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Chinese researchers set up the Experimental Advanced Superconducting Tokamak (EAST) in 2006, which can supposedly sustain a plasma temperature of 100 million degree Celsius for initiating fusion between hydrogen atoms, according to a November 2018 test.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Since the plasma is an electrical conductor, it is possible to heat the plasma by inducing a current through it; the induced current that provides most of the poloidal field is also a major source of initial heating.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The heating caused by the induced current is called ohmic (or resistive) heating; it is the same kind of heating that occurs in an electric light bulb or in an electric heater.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The heat generated depends on the resistance of the plasma and the amount of electric current running through it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] But as the temperature of heated plasma rises, the resistance decreases and ohmic heating becomes less effective.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] It appears that the maximum plasma temperature attainable by ohmic heating in a tokamak is 20–30 million degrees Celsius.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] To obtain still higher temperatures, additional heating methods must be used.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The current is induced by continually increasing the current through an electromagnetic winding linked with the plasma torus: the plasma can be viewed as the secondary winding of a transformer.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This is inherently a pulsed process because there is a limit to the current through the primary (there are also other limitations on long pulses).
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Tokamaks must therefore either operate for short periods or rely on other means of heating and current drive.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] A gas can be heated by sudden compression.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In the same way, the temperature of a plasma is increased if it is compressed rapidly by increasing the confining magnetic field.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] In a tokamak, this compression is achieved simply by moving the plasma into a region of higher magnetic field (i.e., radially inward).
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Since plasma compression brings the ions closer together, the process has the additional benefit of facilitating attainment of the required density for a fusion reactor.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Magnetic compression was an area of research in the early "tokamak stampede", and was the purpose of one major design, the ATC.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The concept has not been widely used since then, although a somewhat similar concept is part of the General Fusion design.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Neutral-beam injection involves the introduction of high energy (rapidly moving) atoms or molecules into an ohmically heated, magnetically confined plasma within the tokamak.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The high energy atoms originate as ions in an arc chamber before being extracted through a high voltage grid set.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The term "ion source" is used to generally mean the assembly consisting of a set of electron emitting filaments, an arc chamber volume, and a set of extraction grids.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] A second device, similar in concept, is used to separately accelerate electrons to the same energy.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The much lighter mass of the electrons makes this device much smaller than its ion counterpart.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The two beams then intersect, where the ions and electrons recombine into neutral atoms, allowing them to travel through the magnetic fields.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Once the neutral beam enters the tokamak, interactions with the main plasma ions occur.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] One is that the injected atoms re-ionize and become charged, thereby becoming trapped inside the reactor and adding to the fuel mass.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The other is that the process of being ionized occurs through impacts with the rest of the fuel, and these impacts deposit energy in that fuel, heating it.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This form of heating has no inherent energy (temperature) limitation, in contrast to the ohmic method, but its rate is limited to the current in the injectors.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Ion source extraction voltages are typically on the order of 50–100 kV, and high voltage, negative ion sources (-1 MV) are being developed for ITER.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The ITER Neutral Beam Test Facility in Padova will be the first ITER facility to start operation.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] While neutral beam injection is used primarily for plasma heating, it can also be used as a diagnostic tool and in feedback control by making a pulsed beam consisting of a string of brief 2–10 ms beam blips.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Deuterium is a primary fuel for neutral beam heating systems and hydrogen and helium are sometimes used for selected experiments.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] High-frequency electromagnetic waves are generated by oscillators (often by gyrotrons or klystrons) outside the torus.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] If the waves have the correct frequency (or wavelength) and polarization, their energy can be transferred to the charged particles in the plasma, which in turn collide with other plasma particles, thus increasing the temperature of the bulk plasma.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Various techniques exist including electron cyclotron resonance heating (ECRH) and ion cyclotron resonance heating.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] This energy is usually transferred by microwaves.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Plasma discharges within the tokamak's vacuum chamber consist of energized ions and atoms.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The energy from these particles eventually reaches the inner wall of the chamber through radiation, collisions, or lack of confinement.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The heat from the particles is removed via conduction through the chamber's inner wall to a water-cooling system, where the heated water proceeds to an external cooling system through convection.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Turbomolecular or diffusion pumps allow for particles to be evacuated from the bulk volume and cryogenic pumps, consisting of a liquid helium-cooled surface, serve to effectively control the density throughout the discharge by providing an energy sink for condensation to occur.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When done correctly, the fusion reactions produce large amounts of high energy neutrons.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Being electrically neutral and relatively tiny, the neutrons are not affected by the magnetic fields nor are they stopped much by the surrounding vacuum chamber.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] The neutron flux is reduced significantly at a purpose-built neutron shield boundary that surrounds the tokamak in all directions.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Shield materials vary but are generally materials made of atoms which are close to the size of neutrons because these work best to absorb the neutron and its energy.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Good candidate materials include those with much hydrogen, such as water and plastics.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Boron atoms are also good absorbers of neutrons.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Thus, concrete and polyethylene doped with boron make inexpensive neutron shielding materials.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] Once freed, the neutron has a relatively short half-life of about 10 minutes before it decays into a proton and electron with the emission of energy.
[src:plasma-physics/tokamak-p02] When the time comes to actually try to make electricity from a tokamak-based reactor, some of the neutrons produced in the fusion process would be absorbed by a liquid metal blanket and their kinetic energy would be used in heat transfer processes to ultimately turn a generator.
